<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: CCI News, Vol #2 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs</h3>
<center><img src="../../graph/cci.gif" alt="CCI News " width=393 height=107 ></center>
<h3 align=center> Volume #2, 1996</h3>
<hr>


<h3>CCI News</h3>
<em>By Jeff Markland</em><p>

Comments from those in attendance indicate that the Competitive Communities Conference held April 3 and 4 in Springfield was a tremendous success.  Attended by mayors; city, county and township officials; economic development practitioners; service providers and local leaders interested in economic development issues, the conference explored the global, national and statewide issues and resources that effect development at the local level. <p> 

Dennis R. Whetstone, Director of the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA), kicked off the conference by sharing with the audience his vision of what economic development is, what it isn't and what needs to be done to make the State of Illinois even more competitive.<p>

Whetstone struck an accord with those in attendance when he said, "Economic development is not synonymous with business development.  Economic development is a much broader continuum of services and activities that have to take place, that if it works, results in economic development."  He went on to define economic development with a formula for success "CD + BD x L = ED" (Community Development + Business Development x Leadership = Economic Development.)<p>

Explaining that in years past DCCA had narrowly defined it's purpose as primarily a business development agency that, by chance, also administered millions of dollars of federal grant and loan funds, Whetstone said, "Today we know to be successful a community needs to do both community and business development, and provide knowledgeable, energetic and professional leadership at the local level."<p>

Five different panels comprised of individuals with varying perspectives discussed  development polices, issues, and practices that are critical to achieving competitiveness in today's market place. <p>

The conference featured panel members from across the nation who came to Springfield to share their perspectives, knowledge and experience with conference attendees.  John Sidor of the Council of State Community Development Agencies; Daphne Clones of the Corporation For Enterprise Development; Don Walls, Walls and  Associates; Martha Lawson, National Associ- ation of Development Organizations; Thomas J. Johnson, Grant Thornton; and Don Tusher, Kelly-Springfield, are just a few of the panel members that brought their years of experience and practical know-how to share with those in attendance.<p>

During his keynote address, Lt. Gov. Bob Kustra stressed the importance of developing our infrastructure, financial resources, technologies, business climate and quality of life.  "By strengthening these foundations we will retain the businesses we currently host, encourage them to expand, and even attract new businesses to within our borders -- bringing new, high quality jobs with them."<p>

One of the five discussion panels, "The Local Experience," showcased the CCI communities of Cairo, Charleston, Oregon and Seneca.  Local leaders from these communities shared the problems  as well as the accomplishments they experienced during their first year as CCI communities. <p>
 
Ron Colson of Oregon said his community used the "dogsled model" -- "We had a lot of people interested but we didn't have a common harness to get us all pulling together in the same direction--CCI gave us that harness."  According to Carolyn Mayberry, "Cairo has been studied to death.  CCI forced us to sit down around the same table and agree on where we wanted to go.  We are now focused and working together."  Charleston Mayor Dan Cougill encouraged communities to get the nay-sayers involved. "You will be surprised at the help you get and the converts that become positive influences within your community," he said.<p>

If there was a common theme expressed throughout the conference by panel members and audience particapants alike, it was the need for accurate, responsive and timely information.  Don Tusher, Plant Manager for Kelly-Springfield, said, "Today we are giving information to our unions that five years ago we didn't give to our managers...if they have the same information we do, they will come to the same conclusions."  The CCI conference was a great opportunity for all of DCCA's development partners to share and exchange information.  We hope that next year you will be able to join us.<p>

<hr>
<h3>MORE ABOUT LAND</h3>
<em>By Rich Funderburk</em><p>

This article addresses what I consider to be the most important ingredient of a local business development program:  land.  If you don't have land, you simply don't have a program.  Your community will be eliminated from any business attraction competition without receiving a visit.<p>  

A piece of land, or "site," is the physical place you have where a business or industry can locate.  A large portion of the evaluation process that a business undertakes will be spent dealing with the physical location -- that piece of land it will acquire and build its facility on.  There are many factors that are taken into consideration when building a new facility on a piece of land that is not completely developed.  <p>

The competitiveness of the site depends on how ready the site is and how well it fits the needs of the prospect.  For example, many sites get eliminated because they just do not have the proper physical characteristics to fit the project.<p>

If your community is going to have a long-term economic development program (covering a period of 15  to 20 years,) then control of land should be a part of that program.  A plan needs to be developed in steps that your community can afford.  Here are the four stages of a site development plan:<p>

The first step is to identify what land in your community is really available for sale.  (Just because you think a piece of land is available or would make a nice site, doesn't mean it is.)  The property owners need to be identified and asked if they are willing to sell and at what price.  <p>

Second, your organization or community can take an option on the property.  That way, if you have the opportunity to negotiate with a prospect, you will have control over what can and cannot be accomplished on the property.  <p>

Third, your community can purchase a piece of land that you control for future development.  I offer a note of caution here.  Before taking title to any property -- especially if it's to be purchased by the city -- make sure it is environmentally clean and there is no remediation that has to be completed (and paid for) after you take over  the property.<p>

Fourth, once you control a piece of property, you should develop a plan for complete development of the site over a long period of time.  This plan will address factors such as infrastructure improvements, roads, sewer, water, rail extensions, etc.  on the land.<p>

Every time you complete one of these steps your community becomes more marketable as a new business location because you are eliminating the unknowns in the process and providing tangibles upon which business decisions can be made.<p>

DCCA has a program called the Select Site program.  It's a very good guide to all of the factors that are evaluated about a site.  And even if you have sites that you don't think will meet all of the guidelines of the Select Site program, it's still a good guide to evaluate what you have.<p>

Developing land is expensive and time consuming.  But it is very important that you take the time to seek counsel from people who can give you advice and help you plan the process so that you make good decisions.  There are many people out there that are willing to help you, if you'll only ask.<p>

Remember, O.I.L. (organization, information, land):  they are the fundamental parts to a local business development program.  If you have these three components, your local economic development effort will have a better chance of success.  Businesses locate in communities; you need to show businesses that you want them and that your community has what they need to locate and grow.<p>


<HR>
