<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Illinois Economic Bulletin, September 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h2 align=center>Department of Commmerce & Community Affairs</h2>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/ieb.gif" alt="Illinois Economic Bulletin" width=575 height=75></center>
<H3 align=center>Vol. 9 No. 3, September 1996</H3>

<hr>

<h3>FAVORABLE  LABOR  MARKET  CONDITIONS</h3>

In a recent news release, the Illinois Department of Employment Security reported that Illinois' total employment exceeded 5.8 million for the first time in January and has maintained that record; the state's unemployment level has been below 5.5 percent for 21 straight months; and Illinois has been at or below the U.S. unemployment level for nearly three years.  They added that payroll expansion over the past year was paced by gains in trade (25,950), services (31,050) and manufacturing (10,500).<p>

Initial jobless claims in the state have continued at a higher rate however. In comparative months, new filings have risen for over a year with only a June decrease. Year-to-date jobless claims are ahead of last year's pace by 30,383 filings or 7.6 percent.<p>

Exports continued their positive growth,  but the pace has moderated from the strong double-digit expansion of the past three years.  Through the first six months of this year, shipments have reached $15.4 billion for an increase of 5.9 percent.  Both manufactured and nonmanufactured goods have posted increases, with the latter recording the largest percentage gain.  The strong demand for grain products and coal has boosted international shipments of nonagriculture products to 48.7 percent above last year's first half level.<p>

According to the Illinois Association of Realtors, the 1996 second quarter statewide median sales price of an existing home rose to $127,600.  This was higher than a year ago by $8,900 or 7.5 percent.  During the quarter, the number of homes sold totaled 27,160, nearly 3,000 more than last year's second quarter.  By locale, average prices ranged from $362,800 in the Barrington area to $153,100 in the Chicago metro market and $34,300 in the Kewanee area.<p>

The number of business failures in the state rose while the amount of losses decreased during the first seven months.  Dun & Bradstreet reported that 1,235 firms in Illinois ceased operations with financial losses to creditors so far this year, compared to 1,072 during the first seven months of 1995.  The size of the liabilities dropped sharply however, declining to $317 million from $455 million last year for a for a 30.3 percent year-to-date descent.<p>

The University of Illinois Flash Index of Economic Growth registered 104.2 in August from 104.9 the previous month.  Its compilers reported that both retail sales and corporate profits in Illinois were lower last month than for August a year ago in real (inflation-adjusted) terms, while personal income rose.<p>

<hr>
<h3>LARGEST  EMPLOYERS  IN  ILLINOIS</h3>

The listing of the top employers within the state was derived from a variety of sources.  Both private and public data bases were utilized with the primary information provided by the Dun & Bradstreet Corporation.  Totals were cross checked where possible with data from Crain's Chicago Business, the Chicago Tribune and the Illinois Department of Employment Security.  The employment estimates are rounded to hundreds and also reflect the total of organizations with multiple locations in Illinois.  A top 15 listing of the largest employers in each county has also been prepared.<p>
  
<hr>
<h3>DRI/McGraw Hill - August - U.S. Economic Outlook - Forecast Overview</h3>

The forecasting firm relates that housing has remained surprisingly strong, despite the rise in mortgage rates.  DRI adds that the recent drop in new home sales suggests that the higher interest rates may be beginning to bite, but sales are still above year-ago levels.  They expect sales and housing starts to drop later this year.<p>

DRI finds that business investment slowed sharply in the second quarter.  They specify that a slowdown in computer sales was a major factor but note that other categories of business investment also softened.  DRI forecasts that computer sales will bounce back later this year.<p>

They relate that employment growth slowed in July but mention that the 193,000 new jobs are still above trend.  DRI feels that the rise in the unemployment rate to 5.4 percent was a correction from the excessive June drop and brings the rate back into the range it occupied for the previous 20 months.<p>

DRI reports that inflation remains calm.  They note that the acceleration in wages is offset by the slow growth of fringe benefit costs.  DRI adds that productivity has been weak during this business cycle.<p>

They relate that export growth weakened in the second quarter, while imports continued to surge.  DRI notes that the higher dollar has had little impact on trade but could keep exports sluggish later this year.  They add that the strong import growth and widening trade gap are caused by the strength of the U.S. economy relative to our trading partners.<p> 


<HR>
