<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS HIGHPOINTS</h3>

  At an estimated $350 billion in 1995, Illinois' gross state product ( GSP ) is fourth among the states.  Compared to other nations' gross national products ( GNP ), Illinois' GSP is larger than all but 12 worldwide. <p> 

  Illinois placed fifth with $32.6 billion in exports last year, and its 23.6 percent annual increase was the largest among the top 10 exporting states.<p>

  Researchers at the University of Illinois recently announced that they have developed a new computer chip which runs faster, and last up to 50 times longer.  The chip making process replaces regular hydrogen with deuterium, resulting in a chip which can handle more electricity, while adding only a small amount to the cost.<p>    

<hr>
<h3>WEFA - MAY U.S. ECONOMIC OUTLOOK - FORECAST OVERVIEW</h3>

  WEFA predicts that the economy's surprisingly strong performance will be sustained for an additional quarter.  They forecast that by the second half of the year, growth will slow to the 2 percent range.  WEFA anticipates that the Federal Reserve will respond by the end of the year with an additional reduction in the Fed Funds rate, because inflation will remain under control.<p>
    
  The forecasting firm notes that the pickup in oil and grain prices cannot create inflation without sufficiently tight labor markets. They add that the Bureau of Labor Statistics employment cost index indicates that wage inflation remains moderate.<p>

  WEFA reports that business investment in equipment will decelerate from its very fast pace since capacity is less imperative at this time.  They anticipate that investment in structures will grow modestly, as businesses build industrial plant and commercial structures in response to low vacancy rates.<p>    

  They predict that the impact of 1995's drop in mortgage rates on the housing market is over.  They add that for the rest of 1996, mortgage rates are likely to drift downward, sustaining housing starts at close to 1.4 million units.<p>

  WEFA relates that despite a poor trade performance in the first quarter, U.S. exports remain competitive.  They forecast that the recovery in Mexico and Japan will allow U.S. exports to maintain high expansion rates, even without strong growth in Europe.<p>

<HR>
