<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS HIGHPOINTS</h3>

  Once again Illinois cities placed high in the National Association of Home Builders fourth quarter 1995 list of affordable housing markets.  Among 192 metropolitan areas Champaign-Urbana ranked 6th, Springfield 13th, Peoria 24th, Rockford 26th and Chicago 129th.<p>

  In 1995, Illinois' 1.13 billion-bushel corn yield ranked second nationally, with its 373 million-bushel soybean crop also placing second and its 68 million bushels of winter wheat output ranked eighth. <p>

  Three Illinois events were selected by the American Bus Association for inclusion in the 1996 Top 100 Events in North America: the Oldsmobile Balloon Classic, Danville, June 7-9; Big River Rendezvous, Moline and Rock Island, October 10-13; and Splendor & Majesty, Rockford, December 6-8.<p>


<hr>
<h3>DRI/McGRAW-HILL -- APRIL U.S. ECONOMIC OUTLOOK - FORECAST OVERVIEW</h3>

  DRI/McGraw-Hill estimates that the economy is heating up.  They predict that the first quarter will be weak, and that spring and summer look stronger than previously expected.  They add that the unemployment rate, at 5.6 percent, is as low as the Federal Reserve is likely to permit, suggesting that the loosening is over for the year.  DRI projects that after a second-quarter rebound, economic growth should stabilize near its trend level of 2.1 percent.  They predict that the Fed will have to tighten by mid-1997. <p>

  The forecasting firm notes that consumer spending, led by automotive sales, has rebounded.  They anticipate that spending will be slower in 1996 than in the past two years, but will keep up with incomes and the Gross Domestic Product.<p>        

  DRI expects housing sales to drop back in response to the recent jump in mortgage rates.  They add that office and motel construction are finally rebounding, while retail and industrial space have accelerated.  They forecast that this trend will continue through 1996.<p>

  They relate that inventories were accumulated even more slowly than estimated in the fourth quarter.  DRI estimates that the level of inventory is still too high, but the General Motors strike reduced much of the excess in the first quarter.  They add that overall, inventories are expected to be less of a drag on the economy in 1996 than in 1995.<p>   

  DRI notes that inflation remains low, in large part because of the sharp slowdown in the growth of fringe benefit costs.  They expect consumer price inflation to accelerate slightly but to remain below 3 percent.<p>

<HR>
