<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Illinois Economic Bulletin, April 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h2 align=center>Department of Commmerce & Community Affairs</h2>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/ieb.gif" alt="Illinois Economic Bulletin" width=575 height=75></center>
<H3 align=center>Vol. 8 No. 10, April 1996</H3>

<HR>
<h3>RECORD RETAIL SALES IN STATE LAST YEAR</h3>

The U.S. Department of Commerce reported that retail receipts in the state exceeded $104.5 billion in 1995 to top the previous year by 4.7 percent.  A preliminary $11 billion December boosted last year's record level as the rate of growth held relatively stable throughout the year.  Sales were particularly expansive in Chicago where they increased 7.4 percent, reaching $15 billion in 1995.<p>

Despite a colder than normal winter, residential building permits in the state are off to their best start in six years.  Through February there were 4,903 construction authorizations issued compared to 4,545 permits a year ago.  The 7.9 percent year-to-date increase continues the slow upward building trend that began last summer when interest rates were reduced.  <p>

The U.S. Department of Labor reported that the Chicago All Urban Consumer Price Index for February rose a modest 1.9 percent from the rate of a year ago.  The news release indicated that medical care costs led the 12 month increase, rising a subdued 2.8 percent.  It was followed by housing expenses and transportation costs that both increased 2.6 percent.  Partially offsetting these categories was apparel and upkeep which declined 2.9 percent during the period.<p>

According to the Illinois Department of Employment Security the state posted record employment for the second consecutive month, reaching 5,829,743 in February.  IDES added that the number of people unemployed in the state dropped 15,483 over the month, from 330,359 to 314,876.  They noted that Illinois' economy demonstrated vigorous growth, adding 121,300 non-farm payroll jobs compared to February 1995 for a 2.2 percent increase.<p>       

In another labor market indicator, initial jobless claims have increased by 28,982 year-to-date.  IDES's data indicates that the upward rate of growth has tapered off and is similar to the 1993 level. During January there were 94,493 first-time filings and 64,020 initial claims in February, which is 22.4 percent above last year's rate.<p>

A recent report by the Administrative Office of the U.S. Courts listed 1,624 business bankruptcy cases in the state last year.  This was 127 less than the 1994 filings for a 7.3 percent decrease.  Business bankruptcies in Illinois have trended downward the past four years as the overall economy has improved.  Nonbusiness filings also were declining until last year when they increased 13.8 percent, totaling 41,147 in 1995.<p>  

The University of Illinois Flash Index of Economic Growth registered 106.1 in March from 107.1 the previous month.  Its compilers reported that after a diminished economic performance in March, the Illinois economy may experience slightly slower growth.  They noted that any reading above 100 indicates future growth of the state's economy.  They added that the current reading suggests a continuation of expansion, although probably at a more moderate rate.<p>  

<hr>
<h3>RECENT INDICATORS</h3>

