<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS HIGHPOINTS</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>O'Hare International Airport in Chicago retained its top world ranking last year by providing service to 67.2 million passengers.  Nearby Lambert Field in St. Louis with 25.7 million travelers placed second internationally for major airport growth with an increase of 10.1 percent.<p>  
<li>Several Illinois universities received a top rating by U.S. News & World Report in their annual educational institutions rankings.  Within the classification of reputation rank by academics" Northwestern University and the University of Chicago received a number one rating (tying for the highest position with several other schools) for their Graduate Schools of Business.  The University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign attained top rankings for its graduate programs in Advertising, Civil Engineering and Library Science.<p>  
<li>A recent edition of Technology Industry Growth Forecaster indicated that Chicago, Oak Brook and St. Charles were among the top 30 cities nationally for telecommunications equipment and services jobs.<p>  
</ul>


<hr>
<h3>WEFA - MARCH U.S. ECONOMIC OUTLOOK - FORECAST OVERVIEW</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>WEFA expects real Gross Domestic Product growth will pick up speed in future quarters   after a two-quarter slowdown.  They estimate that GDP growth will average a little over 2 percent per year from 1995 through 1998.  WEFA adds that most areas of the economy are   weak, with the exceptions of services, business investment and exports.<p>
<li>They project that service employment, demand and wage growth will help steady economic  gains in the future.  WEFA also expects construction employment will rise due to increases in public and nonresidential construction activity.<p>
<li>WEFA forecasts that wages in most service sectors will continue growing more rapidly than manufacturing wages.  They note that international competition will keep costs, including labor costs, down in the manufacturing sector.  WEFA feels that the rising demand for services will continue to push up wages in the services industries.<p>
<li>They predict that business investment in equipment and structures will continue growing more rapidly than the overall economy.  They anticipate equipment spending will expand at a 5 percent pace in 1996 with investments in nonresidential structures increasing about 4 percent.<p>
<li>WEFA estimates that the federal deficit will fall modestly in 1996 as government purchases are down due to the continuing resolutions and the lack of a budget agreement.  They project that government health care costs will rise at a 7 percent to 8 percent rate over the next 10 years.  WEFA also predicts that federal revenue growth will keep pace with income growth.<p>
<li>They forecast that the impact of lower mortgage rates on the housing market is mostly over.  WEFA predicts that a modest decline in mortgage rates and an improvement in employment growth in 1996 will stabilize housing starts at a 1.40 million unit annual rate.<p>
<li>WEFA expects the nation's exports to record robust gains in 1996, led by competitive sectors such as capital goods and industrial supplies.  They anticipate that net exports will add a 0.4 percentage point to the GNP growth in 1996, after subtracting a 0.1 percentage point in 1995.<p>
</ul>



