<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Illinois Economic Bulletin, March 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h2 align=center>Department of Commmerce & Community Affairs</h2>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/ieb.gif" alt="Illinois Economic Bulletin" width=575 height=75></center>
<h3 align=center>Vol. 8 No. 9, March 1996</h3>

<HR>
<h3>ILLINOIS EXPORTS TOP PREVIOUS YEAR'S TOTAL</h3>

Illinois' exports continued their strong growth with over $2.6 billion in direct shipments during November.  The monthly total was the third largest on record, led by manufactured goods that posted their 12th consecutive $2 billion plus month. In just ten months the state's international shipments exceeded the 1994 total and are ahead by 26.4 percent on a year-to-date comparison. The favorable exchange rate and competitive products aided in maintaining the high level of exports. The annual growth rate of shipments from Illinois is nearly double the national rate of increase.<p>

In late February, the U.S. Department of Commerce reported that Illinois' third quarter personal income grew at a 4.8 percent annualized rate for its tenth consecutive quarterly increase.  In current dollars this was a $17.1 billion gain from a year ago and a 6.1 percent increase during this period.  Among the major industrial categories, services led the 12 month advance with an increase of 8.2 percent followed by the wholesale trade with 6.4 percent and finance, insurance and real estate at 5.2 percent.  At the other end of growth, mining posted a 1.2 percent gain as all industrial classifications registered quarterly increases.<p>

The Illinois Department of Employment Security reported that their non-farm payroll survey in January indicated a 140,000 job increase over the monthly level of a year ago. IDES added that the classifications with large gains included 20,400 in business services (which contains personnel supply), 19,000 in manufacturing (4,000 in electronics and 2,900 in fabricated metals), 18,200 in retail trade (13,000 in eating and drinking establishments), 10,800 in engineering and management, 9,900 in wholesale trade, 8,800 in health services, and 7,500 in trucking and warehousing.<p>

After a record year in 1994, contracts for future construction decreased 3.7 percent last year.  The $11.6 billion in 1995 was the state's second highest total, after the previous year's $12 billion.  Last year's amount will likely be revised slightly upward as contracts are expanded and building estimates are exceeded.  The interest rate sensitive construction industry began the year very sluggishly and improved as the rates declined.  The nonbuilding (infrastructure improvements) category dropped the most at 13 percent followed by residential with a 11.3 percent decrease.  Nonresidential construction was positive with a strong 14 percent gain as available industrial space became more in demand.<p>

The Illinois Association of Realtors reported that the median sale price of an existing single-family home in the state last year was $120,500.  This is up more than $5,000 over the 1994 price of $115,300 for a 4.5 percent increase.  Residential prices in the Chicago metropolitan area rose to $146,200 in 1995, topping the previous year by 2.1 percent.  The number of existing home sales in Illinois decreased by 1.1 percent however, after a sluggish start in the first two quarters.  Sales rebounded in the second half of 1995 as lower mortgage rates boosted purchases.<p>
  
The University of Illinois Flash Index of Economic Growth registered 107.1 in February from 106.5 the previous month.  Its compilers noted that all three components of the Index - personal income, corporate profits and retail sales - showed significant growth in February over results for February 1995.<p>

<hr>
<h3>RECENT INDICATORS</h3>

