<li>      <a href="#Activities in a Floodplain">Activities in a Floodplain</a>
<li>      <a href="#Projects Funded with 1996 Program Funds">1996 Program Year Projects to Require Hook-Ups</a>
<li>      <a href="#Program Staff">Community Development Assistance Program Staff</a>
<li>      <a href="#Upcoming Events">Upcoming Events</a>
<li>      <a href="#Announcing Upcoming Fair Housing Workshop">Announcing Upcoming Fair Housing Workshop</a>
</ul>
</h4>
<a name="Intro"><hr></a>
<h3>INTRODUCTION</h3>

Welcome to The Grant Manager.  This is the first issue of a newsletter designed to assist Illinois communities in administering their Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) grants.  We'll be presenting articles on current issues, providing a question and answer section to discuss problems grantees face, and offering a listing of upcoming events.  The Grant Manager will be published at least twice a year.  We hope you will enjoy receiving the newsletter and that it provides you with useful information concerning the Illinois Community Development Assistance Program.<p>

This newsletter is being prepared to assist grantees, administrators, consultants and others who administer CDAP grants.  This is your newsletter and we welcome your questions and comments.  We want to keep an open dialogue of information and knowledge between you and the CDAP staff.  Readers who would like to submit questions for the "Q & A" section or have topics they would like to see discussed in future articles, should submit their written topics or questions to their CDAP Grants Manager.  We will make every attempt to include your information or answer your questions in future newsletters.<p>

We hope many of you attended the 1996 CDAP Application Workshop in February, gaining knowledge about the upcoming program and obtaining copies of the 1996 Application Guidebooks.  If you were unable to attend and would like to receive 1996 Application Guidebooks, please write to Kay Wallwork, Illinois Department of Commerce & Community Affairs, 620 East Adams, Springfield, Illinois 62701, or telephone 217/785-7546; TDD 217/785-6055.<p>

Included in this newsletter is a map and listing of all CDAP staff throughout the state.  This has been included to introduce you to the CDAP staff and their areas of responsibility.  Each edition of The Grant Manager will have a different editorial board to cover a variety of topics.  This edition's editorial board includes:  Jay Bales, Barb Booth, Mike Craig, Pam Jefferies, Sarah Krumrey, and Shirley Watkins.<p>

<a name="Program Changes"><hr></a>
<h3>COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT ASSISTANCE PROGRAM 1996 PROGRAM YEAR CHANGES</h3>

Several areas of the Community Development Assistance Program (CDAP) will experience significant changes beginning with the 1996 Program Year.<p>

<h4>"Accelerated" Funding Cycles</h4>

The 1996 Program Year will begin April 1, 1996 -- two months earlier than the 1995 Program Year -- and all competitive application deadlines will be "moved up" accordingly (See Table I.)  In 1997, it is proposed that the program year would begin January 1st.  Of particular note is the manner in which the Competitive Public Facilities Construction and Design Engineering components will be accelerated for the 1997 Program Year.  As in past years, Competitive Public Facilities Construction and Design Engineering (P/F & D/E) applications for 1996 will be due in July.  In late October, an initial award will be made from those applications, using '96 funds.  And, again in January 1997, a second grant award will be made from the same application "pool", using '97 funds.<p>

For the 1998 Program Year, the P/F & D/E applications will be submitted in October 1997, and grants will be announced in January of 1998.  It is proposed that subsequent years will adhere to this revised schedule of an October submission with January award.<p>

This "acceleration" of the P/F & D/E funding cycle will accomplish several things.  First, spending rates -- of major importance to the U. S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) -- will increase.  Secondly, Illinois will benefit by moving the beginning of its CDAP Program Year to earlier in the calendar year.  Reaching that goal in this particular manner should be of benefit to eligible applicants and their grantwriters:  an extra application submission deadline will not have to be "fit into" the regular rounds; and communities that have frequently been unsuccessful in receiving CDAP grants may receive an award, because, in essence, the awards will be made "farther down the list."<p>

In addition, grantees should benefit from receiving their grant awards in January, giving them sufficient time to complete special grant conditions but not a lot of "waiting time" before construction can begin in the spring.<p>

<h4>Documentation of Threat to Health and Safety of Residents</h4>

For the first time in several years, independent verification of threat to health and safety will not be a requirement of the CDAP Public Facilities Construction and Design Engineering component.<p>

This past year, the CDAP staff have continued to work closely with the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency, and it has become apparent that a letter from IEPA documenting threat to health and safety has become an obsolete requirement.<p>

However, potential applicants are strongly cautioned that the removal of the independent verification requirement in no way lessens the program's emphasis on addressing severe health/safety problems.  There are many ways in which applicants can document a threat to public health and safety, using readily available resources at the local level, which include but are not limited to:<p>
<ul>
<li>     water quality test results
<li>     boil orders
<li>     repair bills
<li>     historical (most recent two years) main break data
<li>     pressure test results
<li>     engineering reports or studies
<li>     complaint letters or data
<li>     historical correspondence regarding sewer treatment plan effluent violations
</ul>

These examples of supporting documentation obviously focus on existing municipal/public systems which are in need of renovation, upgrade, and/or repair.  But what about projects involving new systems which will serve residents on private wells or septic systems?  The following suggestions are offered to strengthen your documentation of a threat to health and safety in those circumstances:<p>
<ul>
<li>      A letter from the local health department which details the problems in the specific target area is recommended.<p>
<li>      Letters or surveys from residents documenting conditions in the target area are suggested to augment the health department letter.
</ul>

Focusing on rural water extension projects, CDAP staff are very aware that private well systems are prone to two distinct problems:  quality and quantity.  In some instances, a target area may even be experiencing both water quality problems and quantity shortfalls.  Both issues are recognized as threats to health and safety under the Public Facilities Construction/Design Engineering component.  Of course, the actual rating that a project receives is dependent upon the level of severity and the extent to which it is documented in the application.<p>

<h4>Low-to-Moderate Income Hook-Ups</h4>

Beginning with the 1996 Program Year, CDAP funds must be used to hook up residential structures which are owned and occupied by eligible low-and-moderate income persons.  A "hook-up" is defined as a privately owned and maintained line on privately owned property between a service lead/connection and a residential structure.  Applicants are advised to plan ahead and include these costs, if applicable, in their CDAP application budgets.<p>

<p>Independent Financial Audits


Under the Competitive Public Facilities Construction and Design Engineering components, a unit of local government's most recent financial audit is required to be submitted along with its application.  A clarification has been added to the 1996 P/F & D/E guidebook, which explains that, when the local government is applying on behalf of a special district (i.e., water or sanitary district), that entity's financial audit should be submitted.<p>

The above areas represent changes that are of significance for the 1996 Program Year.  As always, if you have any questions regarding CDAP in general or regarding the above changes, please feel free to contact the CDAP Grants Manager for your area as shown on the map.<p> 

<h4>
TABLE I.
TENTATIVE CDAP THREE-YEAR FEDERAL PROGRAM YEAR FUNDING PLAN
</h4>
<pre>
<strong>
Competitive                               Program            Application
