<h3>Workshops help Illinois small businesses export</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>One in eight jobs in Illinois is dependent on exporting; one in four in the manufacturing sector. As of 1995, it is estimated that more than 625,300 Illinoisans are employed by jobs sustained by direct and indirect exports.<p>
<li>Every dollar of Illinois exports generates $.04 of state tax revenue.<p>
<li>Export related jobs are globally competitive and proving to be the key to the creation and retention of higher paying and permanent jobs in Illinois. Wages for workers in the manufacturing and service exporting sectors, where Illinois products are the most competitive, exceed the U.S. average by 24 percent.<p>
</ul>


With these figures in mind, Illinois International Trade Centers and NAFTA Opportunity Centers recently hosted a series of workshops throughout the state to help Illinois small businesses export their products to Mexico.<p>

Workshop topics included the use of agent/distributor contracts, labeling and standards, documentation requirements, tips for success. Small businesses who have already been exporting to Mexico, such as Frantz Manufacturing Company in Sterling, spoke about their successes and difficulties.<p>

The keynote speaker at the workshops was Alfonso Cortina, director of the Economist's Conference in Mexico City. At the peak of Mexico's financial crises, he organized a successful roundtable that included the Mexican president and principal ministers.<p>

Cortina said that Mexico is gradually undergoing a transformation of deregulation and private investment that will allow for even greater opportunities for U.S. exports.<p>

With a population of 88 million and a gross domestic product of $377 billion, Mexico is one of our closest and largest trading partners. In 1994, the first year after passage of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), Illinois exports to Mexico increased by almost 38 percent to over $2 billion.<p>

Despite a decline in exports in 1995 after the peso devaluation, Illinois exports are once again on the rise. As of the first quarter of 1996, Illinois exports to Mexico rose nearly 12 percent over numbers from one year earlier.<p>

By 2003 virtually all tariffs on U.S. goods into Mexico will be zero, thus giving U.S. goods a significant competitive advantage over non-North American goods.<p>

"The only sucking sound we've heard since NAFTA passed  is American businesses drinking margaritas after their first sale to Mexico," said Ben Singer, international trade specialist with the U.S. Department of Commerce's NAFTA office.<p>

The workshops were presented as part of the Illinois Export Partnership for Big Emerging Markets and Sectors Project. Funding is provided by the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs' International Business Division through the U.S. Department of Commerce's Market Development Cooperator Program. Future workshops will cover exporting to Eastern Europe and China.<p>

For the location of the International Trade Center or NAFTA Opportunity Center nearest you, call 312/814-7170 or 312/814-2814.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Mandatory electonic tax filing affects many small businesses</h3>
<h4>By Mollie Cole</h4>

<em><strong>EDITOR'S NOTE:</strong></em> Effective July 1, 1997, the Internal Revenue Service will require all businesses depositing more than $50,000 in employment taxes (based on 1995 contributions) to do so electronically.  The start date is January 1, 1999 for those who deposit more than $20,000 in 1997.  The Federal Tax Deposit Coupon will be extinct for businesses required to file electronically. The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) is working with the Illinois Small Business 100, a group of leading small business owners across the state, to examine its impact and see if there are any ways to ease these regulatory burdens.<p>

In 1993 Congress mandated that the Internal Revenue Service use the 1994-1999 period to phase in the Electronic Federal Tax Payment System (EFTPS).  Businesses depositing payroll taxes at or above specified thresholds in certain years will be required to participate in EFTPS.  Once enrolled in the program, businesses shall be required to electronically file all payroll taxes each year regardless of whether or not they ever fall below the initial thresholds.  This eliminates any future use of the Federal Tax Deposit Coupon for these businesses, effective upon the start dates.  Below is the phase-in schedule:<p>

<pre>
<strong>Payroll Tax Deposits     Determination Year     EFTPS Participation
(minimum)                                       Start Date (mandated)  </strong>

$50,000                       1995                   July 1, 1997
$50,000                       1996                   January 1, 1998
$20,000                       1997                   January 1, 1999
</pre>

There are two methods to transfer the funds to the IRS.  The ACH Credit method requires the business to instruct its bank to send payment directly to the US Treasury's account at the Federal Reserve Bank.  The ACH Debit method requires the business to authorize a treasury financial agent to withdraw funds from the business' bank account and route them to the Treasury's account.  Under the credit-based method, the business is responsible for the payment until the Federal Reserve Bank credits the Treasury's account; under the debit-based method, the treasury financial agent is responsible for the payment.  Businesses must apply for enrollment in this program prior to participation.  Application must be submitted no later than two months prior to the businesses assigned start date.<p>

DCCA's Small Business Division estimates that nearly 370,000 Illinois small businesses will be impacted by this federally mandated regulation:  166,200 beginning this July, and an additional 203,000+ by January 1999, the end of the phase-in period.  A significant number (12 percent) of affected businesses are located in manufacturing and seven percent have been in business less than five years.<p>

The majority of businesses, especially those whose participation is required by this July, have already been notified by the IRS of the new policy.  Many businesses reported that they learned of EFTPS through their accountant or bank.  Our Regulatory Alert questionnaire to the Illinois Small Business 100 served as the initial notification for quite a few.<p>

Despite fairly widespread awareness of EFTPS, most businesses are unsure of how this will ultimately affect them and have numerous questions as to what types of adjustments will need to made to be in full compliance.  Many businesses expressed expectations that their local chambers of commerce, financial institutions, and DCCA will provide information and assistance through workshops and instructional materials to help them through this IRS phase-in and implementation.  DCCA's Advocacy Team recognizes this as an excellent opportunity for financial institutions, local chambers of commerce, and DCCA to reach out to the small business community and provide much needed, much sought information and assistance.<p>

Securing status as a treasury financial agent would enable financial institutions to provide their customers with a direct vehicle to utilize the debit-based method of payment.  According to the September 1996 issue of The CPA Letter, only NationsBank and First National Bank of Chicago currently have contracts with the Treasury Department to function in this capacity and can provide this service.  Further, financial institutions offering this service can work with their customers to help identify the best payment method and wade through compliance procedure. <p>

Local chambers of commerce can easily access their relationships with financial institutions and other resources to bring information and assistance to their members through existing schedules of meetings and events.<p>

DCCA's Regulatory Assistance and First Stop offices can work together to develop a technical bulletin that explains the regulations and the steps toward compliance.  DCCA's Small Business Division and Advocacy Team will continue its work through information distribution and the tracking of assistance initiatives throughout the state for resource referral.<p>

<h4>Regulatory Alert Findings</h4>

On September 26, 1996, Regulatory Alert questionnaires dealing with Electronic Filing of Federal Employment Taxes were faxed to the Illinois Small Business 100 (ISB100), with a response deadline of October 2, 1996.  Seventy-nine businesses responded.<p>

Of the 79 responding, more than 63 percent were aware of the upcoming policy. Of those who were aware, most (52 percent) had received the information from the IRS, followed by their accountants, financial institutions and trade/association publications.<p>

Forty-seven out of 79 respondents believe that compliance with EFTPS will require adjustments in bookkeeping methods and will be more costly than current methods. At this time, more than 77 percent of business owners either designate an employee to deposit federal taxes or perform the task themselves.  Over one-third of the respondents expressed concern that implementation would create improper access to company financial accounts and increases in banking service and maintenance fees.<p>

Nearly 52 percent of the respondents reported having questions about the new procedures. An equal amount determined that a technical bulletin, outlining EFTPS policy and procedure would be most useful to their business operations. Almost thirty-seven percent stated that a workshop sponsored by DCCA, a local chamber of commerce or business association/trade organization would enhance their understanding.<p>

<h4>Action Steps</h4>

The ISB100 response to the first Regulatory Alert offers several challenges to the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs.  As a state agency, our impact on a federal regulatory agency is minimal. However, there are several steps we can take to einsure that the Illinois small business community is fully aware of the impact this IRS mandate will have on their future operations.  As of this date: <p>

<ul type=square>
<li>DCCA will meet with staff at Illinois Department of Financial Institutions and the Federal Reserve Bank (Chicago District Office) to request their assistance in addressing your pressing need for current up-to-date information on their ability to electronically process federal payroll taxes.<p>
<li>An easy-to-understand technical bulletin is in development.  The technical bulletin should be available to you by November 5, 1996 on hard copy and located on the DCCA Website at www.ilcommerce.com by November 19, 1996.<p>
<li>Staff are aware of the demand for workshops on the issue of Electronic Filing of Federal Payroll Taxes.  In the next 30 days, staff  will contact appropriate chambers, business associations and trade organizations to determine the feasibility of regional co-sponsored workshops.<p>
</ul>

The Treasury Department is seeking comment on all aspects of the proposed rule, due on or before November 29, 1996, especially on how the rule changes may affect banks' participation in the electronic filing program and their relationship with their customers.<p>

If you would like a copy of the proposed rule, it can be accessed via the Internet at <a href="http://www.ustreas.gov/treasury/bureaus/finman">http://www.ustreas.gov/treasury/bureaus/finman</a>, in the 9/30/96  Federal Register (pp. 51185-51194).<p>

<em>Mollie Cole, manager of DCCA's Office of Women's Business Development, is the project manager of the Illinois Small Business 100.</em><p>

<hr>
<h3>SBDC helps family-owned store survive</h3>
<h4>By Stephen Baise</h4>

In an attempt to bolster the financial viability of their family run business, which as of late has been plagued by disappointing earnings, Bob and Cathy Wiedenhoff explored one of their only remaining sources of help, the Small Business Development Center located at Kaskaskia Community College in Centralia.<p>

Their business, Coast to Coast Hardware, is a franchise type business located in Greenville and has been in operation since 1981. Until recently they had no reason or need for the no services provided by the approximately 40 Small Business Development Centers throughout the state. That was before a major discount competitor moved into the local market, one which had previously been serviced by downtown resident merchants such as the Wiedenhoffs.<p>

Equipped with both fortitude and determination to succeed they decided to seek the guidance and support of Wayne Robke, a professional business and finance specialist at the Small Business Development Center at Kaskaskia College. In conjunction with center director Richard McCullum, the two attempted to alleviate the fiscal dilemma faced by the family by completely analyzing their business operations.<p>

Robke helped develop an updated operation plan. In doing so, he pointed out various avenues to increase profitability by increasing gross profit and decreasing operating cost, such as inventory, labor, advertising, and other overhead expenditures.<p>

Upon further consultation with the Bradford Bank of Greenville and the Coast to Coast franchiser's chief financial officer, Robke explained in great detail the financial considerations that must be approved by all in order that the participating parties benefit from the continuation of this business.<p>

Thanks to the collaboration of the SBDC, the bank, the franchisor and the business principals, the Wiedenhoffs have demonstrated with promising results that entrepreneurs can effectively utilize the many workable resources SBDCs offer.<p>

"We wished we had called two years ago," Bob Wiedenhoff said. "The SBDC has given us the confidence that with our renewed energy and the assistance of others that we regain our past successes and fifteen years of our lives have not been in vain." <p>

<em>Stephen Baise is with the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs' Illinois Small Business Development Network - Office of Network Center Operations.</em><p>


<hr>
<h3>Minority business conference held</h3>
<h4>By Manuel Suarez</h4>

"Minority Business: America's Competitive Advantage" was the theme of Minority Enterprise Development (MED) Week.. <p>

The conference featured a panel discussion where valuable resources and information was disseminated to about 300 participants followed by an award ceremony and reception.<p>

Co-sponsored by the Office of Minority Business Development of the Illinois Small Business Division of the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs, the U.S. Department of Commerce's Minority Business Development Agency, the U.S. Small Business Administration and other economic development organizations, the conference was held at the First National Bank of Chicago.<p>

Honorary chairs for this year event were John F. Timmer, Senior Vice President, First Chicago Bank and Ronald Temple, Chancellor, City Colleges of Chicago.<p>

"This is the period when the Illinois agencies and organizations serving minority and women-owned businesses highlight the success of African Americans, Hispanics, Asian Americans and Native Americans for their contribution to Illinois's economy," said Brian Slaughter, director of the Office of Minority Business Development for Chicago's City Colleges.<p>

MED Week, which began in 1983 by proclamation of President Reagan, is observed in recognition of the contributions and achievements of the country's minority entrepreneurs. <p>

"I am glad to see so many minority businesses at this event. MED Week provides and opportunity for minority entrepreneurs to develop new business leads, increase market potentials through participation in business forums and networking opportunities," said Andrew Ramir, government consultant for Morales, Ramir and Associates.<p>

<em>Manuel Suarez is the Hispanic Business Advocate for the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs' Small Business Division's Office of Minority Business Development.</em><p>


<hr>
<h3>DCCA to co-host ISO 14000 conference </h3>
<h4>By Annette Lingleo</h4>

The Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs' Small Business Environmental Assistance Program will cosponsor a conference to bring together ISO 14000 leaders in the United States for an important discussion of the business, environmental, and regulatory ramifications of the ISO 14000 standards. The conference will be held on November 19 and 20 at the James R. Thompson Center in Chicago.<p>

The ISO 14000 series of standards are voluntary international standards for the establishment of a common world wide approach to management systems that will lead to the protection of the earth's environment while spurring international trade and commerce.<p>

The discussion will focus particularly on the ISO Environmental Management Standards and what they might mean for businesses in the Midwest. It is possible that ISO 14000 may become a condition of some customer/supplier transactions, especially in Europe, Asia, and with the U.S. government. There is also a high probability that the ISO 14000 standards will become a factor in multilateral trade agreements in establishing whether governments are making an attempt to improve the environmental situation within their countries.<p>

The conference is designed to provide an open and active dialogue between speakers and the audience. For more information about the conference, contact ANSI/GETF ISO 14000 Integrated Solutions (IIS) at 703/750-6401 or the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency at 312/886-0180.<p>

<em>Annette Lingleo is Outreach Coordinator for the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs' Small Business Environmental Assistance Program.</em><p>

<hr>
<h3>First-Stop Center expands to ease regulations</h3>
<h4>By Mark Grant</h4>

The First-Stop Business Information Center, a statewide source of regulatory help for business in Illinois, is expanding its role as an advocate for business in government. Already recognized as the first place for a business to call when navigating the maze of state required permits and regulations, First-Stop is expanding its role as a watchdog on proposed legislation and regulations which impact Illinois businesses by including the staff and functions of the Regulatory Flexibility Unit.<p> 

Businesses stated they wanted one place they could call to find out what regulations applied to them and to help them cut through the red tape they often encounter. With that mission in mind, the First-Stop Business Information Center was started one year ago within the Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA).<p>

In the first year, nearly 5,000 individuals have received help with questions or problems with state regulations and starting a business. Response from callers has been very complimentary to the assistance provided. As one caller put it, "I called your 800 number to seek assistance.... the First-Stop specialist was extremely helpful and courteous, and he showed genuine concern and willingness to help," while another caller, "respects and appreciates the level of service and professionalism (they) received from First-Stop."<p>

And now First-Stop is providing another level of help. With the addition of the Regulatory Flexibility Unit, which monitors proposed legislation and regulations, First-Stop helps businesses stay ahead of the regulatory curve. The objectives are to keep the business community as well informed as possible and to act as a business advocate in the legislative and regulatory arena. The Regulatory Flexibility Program, instituted in 1984 and backbone of the Unit, gives First Stop the ability to comment on proposed rules for their impact on small business and make recommendations on how rules can be tiered or even eliminated to alleviate the burden on smaller entities.<p>

Reports summarizing legislative activity are developed on a regular basis during legislative sessions and synopses of proposed rules as published in the Illinois Register every week are available to any interested parties. To receive one or both of these documents, call First-Stop toll-free at 800/252-2923 and ask to speak with Linda Brand. The same information is available on the Web at www.ilcommerce.com. Follow the First-Stop links to Proposed Regulations and Legislation. <p>

Businesses that have concerns can send comments back to First-Stop by phone, fax, letter or through the Internet. First-Stop will follow through with the appropriate legislative and rule making bodies.<p>

<em>Mark Grant is the manager of DCCA's First-Stop Business Information Center.</em><p>

<hr>
<h3>Awards recognize gov't contract help</h3>
<h4>By Lois Van Meter</h4>

Directors of Illinois Procurement Technical Assistance Centers (PTAC) were recognized for their efforts in the contracting arena at their quarterly meeting held in Bloomington. Directors are honored for their personal contribution in helping their clients secure government contracts.<p>

Those winning awards for the fiscal year ending June 30, 1996 are:<p>

Doug Harlan of the University of Illinois' Cooperative Extension Service of Decatur and Dave Talbot of North Business and Industrial Council (NORBIC) of Chicago were each honored with a "million dollar baby," for their first million dollars in contract assistance.<p>

Awards were given for over a million dollars in contract assistance to John DiGiacomo, Rock Valley College, Rockford; Pat Williams, College of Lake County, Grayslake; and Susan Gorman, Illinois Central College, Peoria.<p>

Directors recognized with $5 million contract assistance awards were Tom Halfman, South Suburban College, South Holland; and Ed Van Leer, John Wood Community College, Quincy.<p>

Those receiving awards for $10 million in contract assistance were Harlan and Duffy Toler, College of DuPage, Glen Ellyn.<p>

Receiving awards for $25 million dollars of contract assistance this year are Montrey Balmer, Moraine Valley Community College, Palos Hills; and Elizabeth Scully, Women's Business Development Center, Chicago.<p>

Rich Fyke of John A Logan College of Carterville was honored for helping his client secure over $100 million dollars in government contracts. This is the single highest achievement to date for the PTAC program.<p>

Also receiving $50 million milestone awards were DiGiacomo, Balmer and Pamela See of College of Lake County.<p>

<em>Lois Van Meter is the manager of the Illinois Procurement Technical Assistance Center program.</em><p>

<hr>
<h3>Husband-wife team helps DuPage small businesses</h3>

Like many married couples, Shannon Rielly and Duffy Toler drive each other to work. But for Rielly and Toler, the morning ride takes both of them to the same place: College of DuPage's (COD) Business and Professional Institute in Glen Ellyn.<p>

Rielly has been the director of COD's International Trade Center (ITC) for two and a half years. Toler has been director of the college's Procurement Technical Assistance Center (PTAC) for the past two years and was previously the assistant at the PTAC. They met while working together at COD and were married last year following a wedding proposal on a Washington D.C. vacation.<p>

The couple's strong ties to the state's small business program were humorously illustrated in their wedding program which contained the Illinois Small Business Development Network logo and government-mandated disclaimer language required of all government publications.<p>

Rielly's accomplishments include being named Illinois ITC Director of the Year for the past two years. Toler received $100 Million Milestone Award last year from DCCA, which recognized his efforts in helping secure government contracts for small businesses. He also was honored for reaching the $10 million mark for this fiscal year.<p>

Rielly counsels small and medium-sized businesses interested in exporting their product or service. Specifically, she works with companies to formulate international business plans tailored to their goals and resources, conducts market research to determine target markets, educates companies about export mechanics and identifies overseas contacts.<p>

Toler provides one-on-one counseling for companies interested in doing business with government agencies. He assists companies in identifying the government market for their product or service, provides research to allow companies to formulate a marketing strategy, assists in the completion of bid documents and provides contract management consultation.<p>

Toler says that their professional success "is thanks to a high level of cooperation between our centers," and, adds Rielly, "a healthy level of competition."<p>

<hr>
<h3>Notes</h3>

Pete Ramirez of DCCA's Illinois First program was recently named to the Board of Directors of the Chicagoland Enterprise Center. Ramirez is the former manager of the Illinois Small Business Development Center Network (ISBDCN).<p>

Manuel Suarez of DCCA's Office of Minority Business Development and John DiGiacomo of the Rock Valley College Procurement Technical Assistance Center were awarded the Northern Illinois Minority Contractors Association's Eagle Award for outstanding efforts in Minority Enterprise Development. <p>

Mark Petrilli, ISBDCN assistant state director, was recently named to the Board of Directors of the Illinois Development Council.<p>


