Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Friday, 19-Apr-96 16:37:36 GMT
Content-length: 5312
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Just for Kids -- Coal is Cool!</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#0000A0" LINK="#0000A0" VLINK="#FF0000" ALINK="#FF0000">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>

<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4>

<h3 align=center>
Illinois Coal Fact Sheet<br>
Coal in Illinois
</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>Coal was first discovered in Illinois more than 300 years ago.
<li>Mining began in Illinois more than 200 years ago.
<li>Roughly 54 million tons of Illinois coal are mined annually.
<li>Coal underlies 37,000 square miles of Illinois -- about 65 percent of the state's  surface.
<li>Most of the col is bituminous with high energy values (Btu) between 10,000 and 14,000 Btu/lb.
<li>Illinois' coal reserves contain more Btu than the oil reserves of Saudi Arabia and Kuwait.
<li>Recoverable coal reserves in Illinois (30 billion tons) account for almost one-eighth of the total U.S. coal reserves and one-quarter of the nation's bituminous coal reserves.
<li>Illinois ranks fifth among coal producing states.
<li>It takes less than one pound of Illinois coal to produce one kilowatt-hour of electricity.
</ul>

<hr>
<h3 align=center>Coal Markets</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>$1.5 billion of Illinois coal mined is purchased by the electric utility industry.
<li>About 90 percent of Illinois coal mined is purchased by the electric utility industry.
<li>Over two-thirds of Illinois coal is sold to out-of-state utilities.
<li>The top seven utility users of Illinois coal are: PSI Energy, Illinois Power, Tennessee Valley Authority, Union Electric, Central Illinois Public Service, Northern Indiana Public   Service, and Georgia Power.  All purchase more than 2.5 million tons of Illinois coal annually. 
<li>States in addition to Illinois that use large quantities of our coal include Indiana, Missouri, Florida, Tennessee and Georgia.
<li>Coal-fired power plants generate about half of the electricity used in Illinois.
<li>Decatur-based Illinois Power burns more Illinois coal than any other Illinois user.
</ul>

<hr>
<h3 align=center>Workforce</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>Illinois coal is mined in 18 counties.
<li>In 1994, 32 Illinois mines employed about 6,700 miners and generated roughly 33,000 spin-off jobs.
<li>Coal mining accounts for as much as 16 percent of employment and 23 percent of personal      income in individual counties.
<li>The typical coal miner earns $39,000 per year. 
<li>In 1981, Illinois recorded the first fatality-free year in mining history.
<li>6,700 Illinois miners produce as much coal today as 16,000 miner produced in 1970, 28,000 miner produced in 1950, and 61,000 miners produced in 1928.
</ul>

<hr>
<h3 align=center>Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>The 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments have profound implications for the coal industry in Illinois.
<li>The mandates of the Amendments have triggered fuel switching from Illinois' high-sulfur coal to low-sulfur western coal.
<li>One-fifth of Illinois' 1990 coal production and sales could be lost by the end of 1995 and   as much as one-third could be lost by the year 2000.
<li>In addition, between 3 and 5 non-mine jobs could be lost for each mine job lost.
<li>Some Illinois counties will lose a significant portion of their total employment.
</ul>

<hr>
<h3 align=center>Clean Coal Technologies</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>Illinois' commitment of $138 million towards Clean Coal Technologies (CCTs) has attracted    4200 million in federal funds and $462 million in private and public cost-sharing, supporting 18 clean coal projects within the state.
<li>More than 3 million tons of Illinois' coal production worth $75 million have been sustained   annually as a result of this commitment to CCTs.
<li>Roughly 2,600 mining and non-mining jobs are protected by CCT coal use.
<li>CCT projects mandated by the Illinois state legislature will protect an additional four to five million tons of Illinois coal per year by the year 2000.
</ul>

<hr>
<h3 align=center>Benefits of Scrubbing Illinois Coal</h3>
<ul type=square>
<li>Scrubbing reduces the emissions of SO2 by 90 to 95 percent and can achieve a greater reduction in emissions than with fuel switching.
<li>Burning unscrubbbed western coal produces emissions at a rate of approximately 1 lb. to 1.2   lbs of SO2 for every million Btu of fuel input.
<li>Burning scrubbed Illinois coal could reduce those emissions to somewhere between .3 lbs. and .6 lbs. of So2/miilion Btu.
<li>Scrubbing reduces emissions of other hazardous air pollutants.
<li>Scrubbing Illinois coal saves Illinois jobs.
</ul>

<hr>
For additional information:<p>
<ul>
Department of Commerce and Community Affairs<br>
Office of Coal Development and Marketing<br>
325 West Adams, Room 300<br>
Springfield, Illinois 62704-1892<br>
217/782-6370  TDD: 217/785-0211<p>
</ul>

<hr>
<strong><center>| <a href="http://www.ilcommerce.com"> DCCA Home</a> | <a href="/dcca/menus/kids.htm"> Just for Kids</a> | <a href="../../menus/coalcool.htm"> Coal is Cool</a> |</center></strong>

</h4>
</BODY>
</HTML>
