<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Small Business Financing Options for Environmental Compliance</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Small Business Financing Options for Environmental Compliance</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>
                                   
<center><strong>
Illinois Department of Commerce and Community Affairs<br>
Illinois Environmental Protection Agency<br>
In Cooperation with the Governor's Small Business Environmental<br>
Task Force
</strong></center><p>


This publication is produced in cooperation with the Governors Small
Business Environmental Task Force, the Illinois Department of Commerce and
Community Affairs (DCCA) and the Illinois Environmental Protection Agency
(IEPA).  It is created in response to a recommendation made by the Task
Force to explain existing financing programs that can be used to assist
small businesses in meeting environmental compliance costs.  Specifically
requested were programs available through federal, state, local and other
public sources.<p>

Many sources for financing environmental compliance and pollution
prevention projects exist.  However, few are specifically targeted for that
sole purpose.<p>

It is the intent of this publication to identify the various sources of
financing that exist.  The financing tools (or programs) that exist are
constantly changing.  Therefore, we recommend that you contact the sources
of financing for the current financing programs available to help you
implement your environmental project.<p>


<h3>First Steps to Financial Assistance</h3>

Usually the best source of financial assistance is your local lender.  They
may know about other available programs.  Other organizations to contact
include:<p>
<ol>

<li> local economic development commission<br>
<li> local chamber of commerce<br>
<li> local municipal economic development department<p></ol>

Exploring the availability of local financing resources should be your
first option.<p>


<h3>Information to Take to your Lender</h3>
<ol>
<li> Statement of purpose for the loan<br>
<li> History of your business<br>
<li> Financial information for the last three years, balance sheet, income
     statements for existing businesses<br>
<li> Projections of income, expense and cash flow<br>
<li> Schedule of term debts for existing businesses<br>
<li> Aging of accounts receivable and payable for existing business<br>
<li> Lease details if applicable<br>
<li> Amount of investment in the business by the owner<br>
<li> Signed personal financial statements<br>
<li> Personal resumes<br>
</ul>

<hr>
<center><h3> State & Local Financing</h3></center>
<hr><p>
<strong>
ILLINOIS DEPARTMENT OF COMMERCE AND COMMUNITY AFFAIRS<br>
PARTICIPATION LOAN PROGRAMS</strong>
<p>

The Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) has designed the
Participation Loan Programs to encourage lenders to make loans that they
would not otherwise make for a variety of reasons.  For the purposes of
this program, a lender is an Illinois bank, Development Corporation, or
other lending institution.  By providing financial assistance through local
lenders, the borrower does not need to submit a separate application to the
Department for a loan.  All loan servicing, except some necessary reports,
is handled by the local lender.<p>

Participation loans are purchased when the project being considered has the
potential to create or retain substantial employment  for the people of the
State of Illinois.  The loan can be used for new plant start up,
modernization, expansion or to improve the competitiveness of the borrower.<p>

For current information on this and other state and local programs, contact
the nearest Small Business Development Center (SBDC).  To identify the SBDC
in your area, please call the DCCA Business Assistance Hotline at 800/252-
2923.<p>

<strong>
COMMUNITY DEVELOPMENT ASSISTANCE PROGRAM (CDAP)
</strong>
<p>
DCCA makes grants to local governments, who can in turn make funds
available to local businesses.  The program is targeted to benefit low and
moderate income persons by creating or retaining job opportunities and
improving the quality of their living environment.  Applicants must certify
that 51% of the jobs created and/or retained from the CDAP-funded project
will benefit low to moderate-income persons. Units of local government,
such as cities, villages, townships and counties, may apply for funding.
Municipalities must be 50,000 or less in population and must not be located
in an urban county that receives "entitlement" funds.<p>

For more information, contact your local municipality; local economic
development office or the nearest Small Business Development Center (SBDC).
To identify the SBDC in your area, please call the DCCA Business Assistance
Hotline at 800/252-2923.<p>


Additional contact:  <p>

<blockquote>
Illinois Dept. of Commerce and Community Affairs<br>
Office of Economic Development Programs<br>
620 East Adams<br>
Springfield, IL 62701<br>
217/782-6136<br>
</blockquote><p>

<strong>
COMMUNITY SERVICES BLOCK GRANT LOAN PROGRAM (CSBG)
</strong>
<p>
An existing or potential small business that will employ low-income
individuals is eligible for a CSBG loan.  The business must employ at least
one low-income employee for each $10,000 of the loan amount.  Any new
employees must be hired within the first twelve months of the loan.  The
businesses must also be independently owned, operated and not dominate in
its field; as well as meet size guidelines set by the US. Small Business
Administration.<p>

CSBG loans may be used to finance the purchase of equipment, machinery, or
inventory or to provide working capital.<p>

Contact:<p>
<blockquote>
  Illinois Ventures for Community Action, Inc.<br>
          101 North 16th Street<br>
          Springfield, IL 62702<br>
          217/522-4553<br>
</blockquote><p>

<strong>
ILLINOIS DEVELOPMENT FINANCE AUTHORITY<br>
DIRECT LOAN PROGRAM
</strong>
<p>

Any Illinois business is eligible for this program.  The proceeds must
finance a project that will retain or create jobs in the State of Illinois.
This loan can be secondary to regular financing and can be used to fund the
following fixed-asset projects:<p>

<ol>
<li> purchase of land and buildings;
<li> construction or renovation of buildings; and
<li> purchase of equipment and machinery
</ol>

Contact:<p>
<blockquote>
Illinois Development Finance Authority<br>
Sears Tower<br>
233 S. Wacker, Suite 5310<br>
Chicago, IL 60606<br>
312/793-5586<p>

222 S. College St., Suite 102<br>
Springfield, IL 62706<br>
217/524-1567<p>

400 E. DeYoung St.<br>
Peoria, IL 61602<br>
309/671-0290<p>

124 SW. Adams, Box 397<br>
Marion, IL 62959<br>
618/997-6318<p>
</blockquote>

<hr>
<center><h3>FEDERAL FINANCING</h3></center>
<hr>
<strong> US Small Business Administration (SBA)</strong>
<p>

The federal government, through SBA, provides financial assistance to small
businesses for a variety of purposes.  Many of the programs are in the form
of loan guarantees and are delivered through commercial lending
institutions.<p>

Pollution Control Loan Guarantee Program -  Designed to prevent, reduce or
control air, water or noise pollution.  The program can guarantee up to $1
million on a pollution control loan.<p>

Low Doc Loan Guarantee Program - For small business loans of $100,000 or
less.  The SBA guarantees up to 90% of the loan.  Funds may be used for a
variety of purposes, and the term of the loan is based on the use.<p>

For current information on these and other SBA programs, contact the
nearest Small Business Development Center (SBDC).  To identify the SBDC in
your area, please call the DCCA Business Assistance Hotline at 1-800-252-
2923.<p>


<strong>
US Department of Agriculture - Rural Economic and Community Development<br>
(formerly Farmers Home Administration)<br>
Business and Industrial Loan Program
</strong>
<p>

The Business and Industrial Loan Program (B and I) is designed to assist
eligible public and private organizations in rural areas to obtain quality
loans for the purpose of improving, developing or financing business,
industry and employment as well as improving the economic climate in rural
communities.  A rural community is a city of less than 50,000 and not
adjacent to urban areas.<p>

Contact: <p>
<blockquote>
 US. Department of Agriculture<br>
Rural Economic and Community Development<br>
1817 South Neil Street, Suite 103<br>
Champaign, Illinois 61820<br>
Phone:   217/ 398-5247
</blockquote><p>

District Offices are located in Princeton, Morris, Galesburg, Jacksonville,
Champaign, Flora, Nashville and Harrisburg.<p></body></html>




