<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Labor Management Grant Information</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Labor Management Grant Information</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>

The Illinois Labor-Management Grant Program was established to promote labor-management relations and provide assistance in the development of local labor-management committees.<p>

General revenue funds are appropriated annually to the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs (DCCA) for the Illinois Labor-Management Grant Program to provide grants and other resources to establish and support area labor-management committees and other projects which enhance labor-management relations i the state, its regions, industries and worksites.  The Department, with the advice of the Labor-Management Cooperation Committee, awards grants or matching grants in four areas: (1) to existing local labor-management committees; (2) to developing local labor-management committees; (3) to develop and conduct specialized education and training programs of direct benefit to representatives of labor and management; and (4) for research and development projects related to labor-management issues.  The needs for education and training programs and research and development projects are determined and prioritized annually by the Department with the advice of the Illinois Labor-Management Cooperation Committee.<p>


Types of Local Labor-Management Committees include:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li>Industry Labor-Management Committees generally consisting of associations or coalitions of employers and labor organizations involved in the same industry;<p>
<li>Worksite or Plant Labor-Management Committees comprised of labor and management representatives with activities limited to a particular worksite or facility; and<p>
<li>Area Labor-Management Committees (ALMCs) consisting of a core advisory body composed of representatives from business, labor, government and/or the public, serving a municipal, county or regional population.<p>
</ul>

The Illinois Labor-Management Cooperation Committee makes the determination as to the allocation of funding to the specific grant categories and reviews all grant applications received by DCCA, providing recommendations to DCCA's Director for awarding of grants.<p>

During Program Year 1994 and 1995, the State Committee established priority focus areas for area labor-management committees (ALMCs) including:<p>
<ul type=square>
<li>Facilitate the adoption of worksite labor-management programs by Illinois   private and public sector employers and labor unions;<p>
<li>Increase ALMC programs and services directed toward small and   medium-sized manufacturing firms and public sector employers;<p>
<li>Provide important educational opportunities on major issues affecting the   labor and  management environment (i.e., workshops, seminars and training   sessions);<p>
<li>Develop and conduct programs in conjunction with local school districts to educate  students at all levels on the collective bargaining process and   importance of a labor-management cooperation in the workplace; and<p>
<li>Facilitate the negotiation of special construction project agreements between union building trades and contractor association, promoting the common goals of quality, craftsmanship, teamwork and cooperation within the union construction industry. In FY 1994 and FY 1995, DCCA awarded 23 labor-management grants to support cooperative labor-management programs in Illinois including: 19 existing local LMC grants; three developing local LMC grants; and one research and development project grant.<p>
</ul>

Typical programs and services provided by local committees funded under the Labor-Management Grant Program include: communication facilitation between labor and management assistance in maintaining the competitiveness of union contractors; program promoting job retention and skill training; information and assistance for displaced workers; assistance and participation in various economic development activities; educational workshops; specialized training programs; and technical assistance services to employer/employee organizations.<p>


<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/files/wforce/labor.htm">Labor Management Grant Program</A> |</STRONG>
</BODY>
</HTML>
