<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Labor Management Workplace Benefits</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#8080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/logosm.jpg" alt="DCCA Logo" width=165 height=82 align=left>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<h3>
Department of Commerce & Community Affairs<p>
</h3>
<img src="/dcca/graph/cbar.gif" width=410 height=4><p>
<FONT SIZE=+3>Labor Management Workplace Benefits</FONT>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>
<HR>
<p>
<img src="/dcca/graph/lmwp1.gif" width=261 height=328 align=right>


<img src="/dcca/graph/lmwp2.gif" alt="Cooperative Workplace Program" width=98 height=57 align=left vspace=5 hspace=10>

A proven method to enhance the labor-management environment at the workplace is through implementation of cooperative program addressing issues such as worker safety, product and service quality, working conditions and overall labor relations.<p>

<hr>

<center><img src="/dcca/graph/lmwp3.gif" alt="Most Common types of Cooperative Programs" width=97 height=55></center>
<ul>
<li>Worksite Labor-Management Committees are flexible committees usually comprised of an equal number of labor and management members.  A committee contains both labor and management representatives and meets periodically to identify and discuss opportunities to improve production methods and resolve problems affecting both parties.<p>
<li>A worksite committee is a vehicle to increase communication.  It can provide an effective response to challenges facing the plant or worksite.<p>
<li>Employee Involvement Programs  seek to engage all employees in an effort with management to achieve goals such as product improvement, cost-cutting or some other goal.<p>
<li>Quality Circles involve 6-12 employees in regular meetings to discuss how to improve production techniques and the work environment.<p>
</ul>

A substantial proportion of Illinois firms utilize cooperative labor-management programs as part of the routine conduct of business.<p>

A LABOR-MANAGEMENT PARTNERSHIP/COOPERATIVE WORKPLACE PROGRAM ENABLES LABOR AND MANAGEMENT TO WORK AS PARTNERS OR EQUALS IN RESOLVING PROBLEMS/ISSUES AND DEFINING THE FUTURE DIRECTION OF THE ORGANIZATION.<p>

<strong>What's in it for Labor?</strong><p>

1. Involvement in decision making.<p>
2. Improvement in communication and overall relationship.<p>
3. Access to organization information.<p>

<strong>What's in it for Management?</strong><p>

1. Productivity gains through efficient use of resources.<p>
2. Improved communication and unified access to all unions.<p>
3. Improved quality, decentralization and support in decision making.<p>

<hr>
<img src="/dcca/graph/lmwp4.gif" alt="Tips for Survival" width=100 height=61 align=right>
<ul>
<li>The leadership of both sides must want this procedure to be effective.
<li>Both parties must be genuinely open to working on a wide range of   problems.
<li>Channels of communication should always be kept open.
<li>Both parties must report back to their respective group the problems   considered at meeting and how issues ate to be resolved.
<li>The parties jointly own the partnership and are responsible for making it   work.
<li>Success requires a willingness to listen to the opposite side.
<li>Parties must concentrate on the problems at hand instead of past   differences.
</ul>

<hr>
<img src="/dcca/graph/lmwp5.gif" alt="Labor-Management Partnerships" width=104 height=61 align=left vpsacw=5 hspace=10>

A means of increasing both communication and understanding between labor and management is to establish labor-management partnerships.<p> 

These partnerships, composed of key leaders chosen by both labor and management, first discuss the concepts and expectations of a joint labor and management partnership.<p>

The establishment of a labor-management committee is an important step in implementing a workplace program.  The focus of these programs often is on quality of work life, human resource utilization, safety, productivity and quality improvement.<p>

Structurally, these efforts vary significantly.  Some are operated by a steering group with satellite participation teams, and some are confined to the shop floor.<p>

Participants in joint labor-management efforts report that when labor and management tackle problems together, not only are they more successful in solving their problems, but the solutions are more widely and readily accepted by all.<p>

It is important that the parties realize that this is only the first step, and they should dedicate themselves to working hard to make this  procedure work.<p>

<hr>
<img src="/dcca/graph/lmwp6.gif" alt="How Can You Get Started?" width=97 height=56 hspace=10 vspace=5 align=left>

There are a number of Illinois Area Labor-Management Committees (ALMCs) and professionals available to provide the necessary training and technical assistance to organizations interested in starting cooperative workplace programs.<p>

For more information on assistance and available resources or the location of the ALMC nearest you, contact the Labor-Management Cooperation Unit at the Department of Commerce and Community Affairs by phoning 217/785-6215; TDD 217/785-6055.<p>


<HR>
<STRONG>| <A HREF="http://www.ilcommerce.com">DCCA Home Page</A> | <A HREF="/dcca/files/wforce/labor.htm">Labor Management Grant Program</A> |</STRONG>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
