<HEAD><TITLE>DCCA: Trade Leader Newsletter, Fall 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000080" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#8080C0" ALINK="#004080">

<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs</h3>
<center><img src="/dcca/graph/tl.gif" alt="Trade Leader" width=572 height=100></center>

<center><font size=+3>Fall 1996</font></center>
<BR CLEAR=RIGHT>

<hr>

<h3>ILLINOIS IS SERIOUS ABOUT INTERNATIONAL TRADE</h3>

South African International Trade Exposition, SAITEX `96 (Made in USA `96)<br>
Johannesburg, South Africa<br>
October 22-26, 1996<p>

South Africa is one of the world's dozen or so "Big Emerging Markets" U.S./Illinois firms are turning to. For years, apartheid kept U.S. companies out of South Africa, but political reform and the promise of political stability are quickly turning the once-taboo nation into a hot market.<p>

The United States now ranks as South Africa's leading trading partner. More than 300 U.S. companies have made significant investments in South Africa since the lifting of the U.S. sanctions. The two nations launched a commission to foster improved business relations in March of  1994. In 1995, Illinois exports to South Africa grew 44.3% over the previous year. This growth earned South Africa's place as one of the top 25 countries receiving Illinois exports.<p>

After experiencing a successful promotion in South Africa's 1995 Made in USA exposition, Illinois' DCCA International Business Division elected to return in 1996 with an even larger group of Illinois companies. A contingent of 48 Illinois firms will receive exposure to the South African market at this event. This is the largest U.S. export trade promotion event in South Africa where more export leads are generated in five days than most companies see in a year.<p>


SAITEX `96 (Made in USA 96) success is largely due to a U.S. Department of Commerce grant provided to DCCA's International Business Division, which in effect helped defray partial booth costs for participating Illinois companies. This program is presented as part of the "Illinois Export Partnership for Big Emerging Markets and Sectors Project" and has proved to be a very cost effective means for penetrating one of the world's "Big Emerging Markets".<p>

<hr>
<h3>ILLINOIS TRADE FORECAST - OUTLOOK 1997</h3>

Illinois' export growth continues to outpace the nation as a whole. In 1995, Illinois exports increased to $32.6 billion, representing a 23.6 percent increase over the previous year, and placing Illinois ahead of the national growth rate of 13.8 percent. This growth is expected to continue for a variety of reasons, most important being Illinois' ability to supply products to the world's most active and growing economies in key country development sectors. These sectors encompass core materials-industrial and capital goods that are essential to building the infrastructure of the world's developing nations. One trend is clear: Companies that make the leap into export are growing faster than others.<p>

Exports from Illinois surged 23.6 percent in 1995 to $32.6 billion. Illinois export figures have a proven track record for being competitive and Illinois export growth was double the national average in 1995. The type of products and services that Illinois is sending abroad provides the key to Illinois' future export growth. More than 70 percent of Illinois' exports are in high-technology sectors such as electronics, computers, and transportation equipment. Illinois' export growth in 1995 in electronics (41.7 percent) and industrial equipment (15 percent) remained strong and is predicted to grow throughout 1996. In fact, Illinois' growth in the electronics and other high tech sectors nearly doubled that of the national average in 1995. As the global market continues to modernize, Illinois' competitive advantage in those and other high-tech industries will continue to be tapped, increasing the number of value-added jobs in the state. Simply defined: Illinois' success in exporting comes from producing high-quality products, mainly capital goods, for the highly competitive world marketplace.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Exports are a Vital Component of our State's Economy</h3>
<ul>
<li>	One in eight jobs in Illinois is dependent on exporting; one in four in the manufacturing sector. As of 1995, it is estimated that more than 625,300 Illinois residents are employed by jobs sustained by direct and indirect exports.
<li>Every dollar of Illinois exports generates $.04 of state tax revenue.
<li>Export related jobs are globally competitive and proving to be the key to the creation and retention of higher paying and permanent jobs in Illinois. Wages for workers in the manufacturing and service exporting sectors, where Illinois products are the most competitive, exceed the U.S. average by 24 percent.
<li>Illinois ranked 5th in the nation among the top ten exporting states in 1995; this is the second consecutive year that Illinois has improved its ranking. Illinois export growth is evidenced by double digit export increases in 1993, 1994, and 1995: 24.6 percent, 20.2 percent and 23.6 percent respectively. 
<li>Illinois exports reached an all-time high of $32.6 billion in 1995, an increase of 23.6 percent over 1994 and nearly double the 13.8 percent increase of all U.S. exports for the same period 
<li>Exporting companies pay employees more than plants that produce only for domestic consumption.
<li>Worker productivity at exporting companies is 30 to 50 percent higher than that of non exporters.
<li>Innovation is stronger at exporting companies. Exporters adopt new technologies far more frequently than non exporters and report more significant benefits from doing so. This tendency is especially strong in fabricated metal products, machinery, computers and transportation equipment-key industrial sectors in Illinois
<li>Exporting companies tend to be larger than others, on average four times as large in employment and six times as large in sales.
<li>Sales per employee tend to be 50 percent greater in exporting companies than in non exporting companies.
<li>Value added per employee is up to 33 percent greater in exporting plants than in non exporters.
</ul>

<hr>
<h3>Illinois' Global Future:  The Underlying Structure</h3>

Some of the factors that account for a positive global outlook for Illinois and those relating to Illinois' continued status as an export driven economy are the fact that:<p>

1)	Illinois exports less of its gross product than the U.S. as a whole, indicating that opportunities for increased exports will continue to exist over the long haul.<p>

2)	The world market is four times larger than the U.S. market, and is predicted to grow as much as 40 percent faster than the U.S. market through the year 2000. The industrial centers and targeted industries within Big Emerging Markets (markets that will account for the overwhelming incremental growth in world imports over the next decade) are predicted to grow even faster.  Illinois already has a strong track record in many of the world's most explosive markets, indicating even greater economies of scale are expected from Illinois firms exporting to those rapidly growing economies.<p>

3)	Illinois produces what the world's most rapidly growing economies need- industrial machinery, telecommunications equipment, electronics, financial services, and products related to the needs of basic economic development. In other words, the products and services need to build a strong infrastructure and economy.<p>

The following are some market trends to watch throughout 1996 and 1997:<p>

Big Emerging Markets: What Are They and Where are They?<p>

Big Emerging Markets or BEMs are the markets that will double their share of world imports (and imports of Illinois products), rising 38 percent by 2010. No other category of market shows such dramatic growth potential.<p>

The BEM markets provide overwhelming opportunities for Illinois exports. While the markets of Europe and Japan continue to be among the top 10 trading partners for Illinois firms, current trends demonstrate slower growth in these traditional markets than in the BEMs. Most of the BEMs now rank among Illinois' top 10 trading partners, and are at least among the top 25 world markets for Illinois products.<p>

The BEMs are unlike Illinois' more traditional trading partners, such as Japan, Great Britain or Germany. There are frequently still trade barriers to entering those markets, and full respect for commercial systems are often still developing or lacking altogether. The nature of competition we face in these market is dramatically different from prior experience and they have economies that are growing twice as fast as the rest of the world.<p>


<h4>The Big Emerging Markets</h4>

The Chinese Economic Area (China,Hong Kong and Taiwan)<br>
South Korea<br>
The Association of' Southeast Asian Nations or ASEAN<br>
India<br>
Mexico<br>
South Africa<br>
Brazil<br>
Poland<br>
Argentina<br>
Turkey<br>

<hr>
<h3>Look for Growth In Major Trading Blocks such as ASEAN</h3>

There are six countries whose combined GDP is likely to reach $1.1 trillion in little over a decade. And by that time, U.S. exports to the region where these countries are found will probably equal or exceed exports to China or Japan. The ASEAN region-consisting of Brunei, Indonesia Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam-has become one of the most dynamic economic areas of the world. The reasons: rapid growth, expanding purchasing power and falling trade barriers.<p>

Growth, and the problems it creates, is generating extraordinary opportunities through out Southeast Asia. Increased demand for and expenditure on quality housing, environmental concerns and health care-generating new markets for technologies are emerging along with regional economic success. Breakneck growth is straining every kind of infrastructure, creating what is perhaps the best single market for Illinois goods and services.<p>

1Figures derived from the Washington Based Institute for International Economics, the National Association of Manufacturers, and the Massachusetts Institute for Social and Economic Research.<p>

<hr>
<h3>Export Tips</h3>
<h4>EXPORTERS BEWARE</h4>

The following contribution is provided by LaSalle's Foreign Exchange Department.<p>

As the world moves toward a true global economy, U.S. exporters need to rethink their U.S. dollar invoicing strategy.<p>

When exporters strictly invoice in U.S. dollars they may think that they do not have foreign exchange risks. This is not true.<p>

By invoicing in U.S. dollars, U.S. exporters do not bear actual conversion risk but are susceptible to movements in exchange rates. As the U.S. dollar increases in value vis a vis foreign currencies, U.S. goods become more expensive abroad.<p>

The following is an example of what can happen: Let's assume the U.S. dollar/deutsche mark exchange rate is 1.54-this means that the German customer will need to give up 1.54 deutsche marks to purchase one dollar. If the exchange rate goes up to 1.60, the German customer needs to pay 1.60 marks to receive the same one dollar. The cost of doing business with a U.S. exporter just increased by almost 4%. If the German customer can find another supplier with the same or similar product that is willing to price goods in deutsche marks, the U.S. supplier will most likely lose the business.<p>

The majority of U.S. exporters still invoice in U.S. dollars. In order to maintain a competitive position in the global market, you should come aware of the advantages and disadvantages of local currency invoicing.<p>

To learn more about local currency invoicing and how to manage foreign exchange exposure, please contact Camille Rudge, Vice President and Foreign Exchange Manager, at (312) 904-2827.<p>

<hr>
