<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Lawn Care Containment Permit</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Lawn Care Containment Permit
</DD></DL>
	
<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
Bureau of Environmental Programs<BR>
P.O. Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 785-2427<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
425 Illinois Compiled Statutes 65/1-8.  (Lawn Care Products Application and Notice Act.)
</DD></DL>

<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A Permit is required to operate a commercial lawn care companies or a golf course.  A Permit authorizes the application of lawn care chemicals.  A permit is required for the construction and operation of a "wash water containment area" at the business's facilities.  Conducting business without a Permit may result in fines of between $100 to $500.  Permits are valid for 5 years.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.   Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must complete and file an "Application for Permit & Construction Approval Lawn Care Containment Facility".   The application requires technical information and drawings, including a map of the facility and the surrounding area, a water/well protection plan, operational and management practices plan, engineering plans and specifications, the collection and recovery system flow diagram, storage facilities, and more. Denied applications may be appealed under the terms of the Administrative Review Law.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permit holders are required to give notice of chemical applications by placing a 4" x 5" marker where  lawn care products have been applied.  The facility must pass an inspection by the Department.  Applicators must be licensed by the Department under the Illinois Pesticide Act.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>


<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
