<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: License for Grain Dealers Who Buy from Farmers</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
License for Grain Dealers Who Buy from Farmers
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
Bureau of Warehouses<BR>
P.O. Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 782-2895<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
111 Illinois Compiled Statutes 301-312.  (Illinois Grain Dealers Act.)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A license is required for businesses that buys grain from farmers (producers) for resale, milling or processing.  Doing business as a grain dealer without this license is a Class B misdemeanor for the first violation and a Class A misdemeanor for subsequent violations. The license is for one fiscal year and expires 90 days after the end of the fiscal year.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.   Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must complete and file a Grain License Application, giving.  The names of the officers and partners, location of the office and all facilities, the fiscal year of the operation, the kind of grain to be bought and handled, and financial information.  A surety bond must be filed with the Department.  Upon receipt of a complete application and bond, the Department will promptly process the application.<P> 

Applicant must be of good business reputation, be qualified to be a grain dealer and may be required to participate in training programs, pay all necessary assessments set forth in the Illinois Grain Insurance Act and file the required bond or certificate of deposit.  The most common reason for denial is for failure to meet the financial requirements.  There is no appeal process following a denial.<P>  
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Facilities must be open from 1/2 hour before the open to 1/2 hour after the close of trading at the Chicago Board of Trade.  License holders must maintain accurate, current long and short market position records for each commodity.  The Department may require licensees to post additional collateral security.  The licensee must carry insurance on all company-owned grain.  Licensees must give inspectors access to all books, accounts, and papers during business hours.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The fee for the license is $50.  The fee for additional locations and/or each truck to be used by a grain dealer is $10.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
