<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: License for Refrigerated Warehouse.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I. Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
License for Refrigerated Warehouse.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
Bureau of Animal Welfare<BR>
P.O. Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 782-6657<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
240 Illinois Compiled Statutes 35/1-13a. (Illinois Refrigerated Warehouse Act)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
This license is required to operate a facility where food or drink is stored and held under 45 degrees Fahrenheit for 30 days or more prior to distribution to wholesalers, retailers or jobbers, not including locker plants.  The license authorizes a business to maintain or operate a refrigerated warehouse.  Operating a refrigerated warehouse without  license is a business offense and may be fined from $500 up to $10,000 for each offense.  The license is valid for one year.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must complete and file an "Application for a License to Operate a Refrigerated Warehouse", describing the location, sanitary conditions, capacity, and method of refrigeration of the warehouse.  The Department will inspect the facility before a license will be issued.<P> 

If the facility doesn't pass inspection, the applicant may enter into a Work Progress Agreement with the Department. (A Work Progress Agreement describes the specific things that must be done to satisfy Department inspection requirements.)   Inspections generally take 3-4 weeks, after which a license will be issued.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
License holders must give Department inspectors access to refrigerated warehouses.  Licensees must meet all local zoning requirements and comply with the Assumed Name Act.  No article of food unfit for human consumption may be put into the warehouse without being marked plainly that it is not to be sold or used for human consumption.<P> 

All articles of food must be identified and stamped with a lot number before it goes into storage, and proper records of all lot numbers must be kept.  Maximum time for storage is 24 months, except with written approval.  License holders may not describe food as "fresh" if it has been refrigerated more than 29 days.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
The fee for the license is $50.00
</DD></DL>


<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
