<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Notification of Intent to Drill a Well & Registration of the New Well.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Notification of Intent to Drill a Well & Registration of the New Well.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Agriculture<BR>
Bureau of Soil & Water Conservation<BR>
P.O. Box 19281<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9281<BR>
(217) 782-6297<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 345 (Water Use Act of 1983)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Any business (such as golf courses, orchards, nurseries, crop production or any business using  large amounts of water) planning to drill a water well with an expected use of 100,000 gallons a day must notify the local Soil and Water Conservation District of its intent to be a substantial user of water.   In the counties of Kankakee, Tazwell, Iroquois, and McLean, businesses must register any new well.<P> 

In  emergencies (such as drought) the Department has authority to restrict groundwater withdrawals in those 4 counties.  Failure to notify the Soil and Water Conservation District of a proposed new point of withdrawal (a well), or any business failing to register a well in the 4 counties named above, or a business failing to restrict withdrawals if required to do so by the Department, is guilty of a petty offense.  If convicted more than once, violations become a Class C misdemeanor.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Notice to the local Soil and Water Conservation District Office of the intent to be a substantial user of water may be by phone or in writing, but must be given before  construction of  the well begins. The Soil and Water Conservation District then notifies the Illinois State Water Survey, which conducts an investigation to determine the impact the proposed groundwater withdrawal may have on other water users.  The conclusions of that investigation are published in a general circulation newspaper. The Soil and Water Conservation District informs any local units of government that might be affected by the proposed groundwater withdrawal.  The review must be completed within 30 days of receipt of the notice. 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A permit to drill a well is required by  Illinois EPA and Department of Public Health statutes. The drilling company normally complies with those requirements (although it is the responsibility of the business to be sure that they do) and to provide a "well log" to the State Water Survey.   The business must make pumping data available and allow the Department and/or Soil and  Water Conservation District employees access to private property to conduct investigations.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
