<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Construction & Operating Permits for Pollution Emission Units</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement  Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Construction & Operating Permits for Pollution Emission Units
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Environmental Protection Agency<BR>
Bureau of Air / Division of Air Pollution Control<BR>
1340 North 9th Street<BR>
Springfield, IL 62702<BR>
(217) 782-7326<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
415 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/1 et seq (Environmental Protection Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
35 Illinois Administrative Code 201.142-144
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permits may be required of any business that has emission units (stationary equipment, operations and associated control systems) that have the potential to emit any regulated air pollutant (particulate matter, volatile organic material, and nitrogen oxide). Businesses usually required to have these permits are steel mills, manufacturing plants, electric utilities and chemical plants, as well as certain smaller businesses like hospitals, dry cleaners, grain terminals, print shops and electroplating shops. <P>

Construction Permits are required for the construction of new
emission units and modifications to existing units if those
changes increase emissions, and are valid for 1 year. <P>

Operating Permits  include four (4) types:  Smaller Source
Permit, State Operating Permit, Federally Enforceable State
Operating Permit (FESOP) and Clean Air Act Permit (CAAPP).  The
type of operating permit needed depends upon the amount of
regulated pollutants emitted and the geographical location of
the business and commonly are valid for 5 years. To determine
which Permit is needed, ask for "Does Your Business Need an Air
Pollution Control Permit?", from the Agency.<P>

If both are applied for at the same time, they both commonly are
valid for 5 years. Operating without a Permit may result in
fines.  Permit holders failing to comply with the Act are
subject to penalties that vary with the severity and duration of
their actions.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Construction Permits and Operating Permits Permit applicants must submit an application package, consisting of a plot plan/map, appropriate application forms for the specific operation, all relevant drawings, calculations and
other pertinent data, to the Bureau of Air. The Agency is allowed 90 days to respond to applications when public notice is not required.  However, when public notice is required (e.g., FESOP, CAAPP & significant or major construction), the Agency is allowed 180 days or more to respond. Permit applications are reviewed by Agency engineers and are approved if the application shows that the emission units comply with all applicable air pollution control regulations. <P>

Applications can be denied if non-compliance is shown or if insufficient information is provided in the application. Permit denials can be appealed through the Pollution Control Board. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permits may require record/report keeping.  Annual Emission Reports are required by May 1 of each year for every facility that has an Operating Permit.  Site fees must be paid before a new Operating Permit will be granted to a facility.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Annual site fees are based on the amount of permitted or allowed emissions.<P>

<STRONG><EM>Total permitted emissions less than 25 tons/year:</EM></STRONG> $100.  <P>

<STRONG><EM>Sources with total emissions of 25 tons/year or more, but less than 100:</EM></STRONG>  $1,000. <P>

<STRONG><EM>Sources with total emissions of 100 tons/year or more:</EM></STRONG> 
$13.50/ton up to a maximum of $2,500/year (excluding carbon
monoxide (CO) and chloroflorocarbon (CFC) emissions).  <P>

<STRONG><EM>FESOP fee:</EM></STRONG> $1,000. CAAPP fee: Minimum $1,000; $13.50 per ton up
to a maximum of $100,000.<P>
</DD></DL>


<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
