<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Landscape Waste Composting Permits</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I. Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Landscape Waste Composting Permits
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Environmental Protection Agency<BR>
Bureau of Land / Permits Section <BR>
1340 N. Ninth St.<BR>
Springfield, IL 62703<BR>
(217) 524-3300<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
415 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/1 et. seq.<BR>
(Illinois Environmental Protection Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
35 Illinois Administrative Code 830-832 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A Permit is required before a new Landscape Waste Composting facility may accept waste for composting, or before an existing Landscape Waste Composting facility can be modified to accept landscape waste for composting.<P>

The permit allows a facility to accept only landscape waste and only for the purpose of composting. <P>

A business operating without a permit is subject to enforcement action, which ranges from requiring compliance to a jail term, and fines. Enforcement action and fines vary in severity and duration according to the violation. <P>

A permit may be valid for a maximum term of 5 years, and may be renewed.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants for a Permit must complete and file forms LPC-PA1, LPC-PA12 and LPC-PA16.<P>

The application must be signed and bear the seal of an Illinois licensed professional engineer. <P>

The processing time for applications for renewal or modification of existing facilities takes 90 days.<P>
 
The processing time for applications for new or expanding facilities is 180 days.<P>

Applications are most commonly denied because of technical deficiencies found in the application. <P>

Denied applications may be appealed to the Pollution Control Board. 	<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Quarterly reports are required of information including data on groundwater/surface water monitoring and other information as may be required in the Permit. (IEPA determines what information will be required  according to the unique circumstances dictated by each application.)<P>

Annual reports are required of information including the volume of waste received at a facility, and other activities specified by the Agency.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
