<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Permit for construction within rivers, lakes and streams in Illinois</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I. Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permit for construction within rivers, lakes and streams in Illinois
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Environmental Protection Agency<BR>
Division of Water Pollution Control<BR>
2200 Churchill Road<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9276<BR>
(217) 782-0610<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
415 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/4
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 35 Illinois Administrative Code, Subtitle C, Chapter II, Part 395, Procedures and Criteria for Certification of Applications for Federal Permits or Licenses for Discharges into Waters of the State.
</DD></DL>

<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A license, a permit and/or a certificate is required for projects that will cause a discharge into streams, wetlands or other bodies of water.  Federal permits are issued by the Corps of Engineers under the Dredge and Fill program.  Licenses are issued by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission for hydroelectric power facilities.  Certificates issued by the Agency confirm that a proposed project may be constructed and operated in compliance with the applicable water quality standards established by the State.  Dredging, placement of fill, draining or other similar actions in streams, lakes, canals and adjacent wetlands must be authorized by the Corps of Engineers and the Agency under the Section 404 and 401 permit/certification program.  Causing a discharge into streams, wetlands and other bodies of water without the proper permit is subject to fines up to $50,000 plus $10,000 for each day the violation continues.  Permits remain effective until a project is completed.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file a "Protecting Illinois Waters" form including a description of the proposal and copies of plans and drawings of the project with the Corps of Engineers.  For projects requiring an individual permit, the Corps will issue a public notice jointly with the Illinois Department of Transportation and the Agency describing the project and offering the public an opportunity to comment and to request a hearing on the matter.  At the end of the public notice period the Agency will review all comments and evaluate the water quality aspects of the proposal.  If disputed issues arising from the impact of the proposed project and the public can be resolved, certification will be issued, usually within 30 days of the end of the public notice period.  The Corps usually acts within 3 to 6 months after an application is received.  
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Additional Agency permits may be required for sanitary sewers, water mains, landfills and other treatment facilities.<P>

Projects involving dredging and disposal of sediment in a confined facility may require an analysis of the dredged material as a part of the application, and monitoring of the facility effluent is usually required to ensure compliance with the water quality standards.  <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
