<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Permit for installation, changes or additions to a Community Public Water Supply (CPWS)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I. Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permit for installation, changes or additions to a Community Public Water Supply (CPWS)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Environmental Protection Agency<BR>
Division of Public Water Supply<BR>
2200 Churchill Road,  P. O. Box 19276<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9276<BR>
(217) 782-1724<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
415 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/15,16 and 39.
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
35 Illinois Administrative Code 602.101-104, & 35 IAC 690.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Permits are required to construct and operate a community public water
supply (CPWS) that serves 25 or more residents or that has 15 or more
residential service connections. (The Illinois Department of  Public Health
regulates smaller water supplies.)  A permit may be issued only to an owner
or official custodian in charge of the water supply.  The purpose of a
permit is to insure that installations, changes or additions to a CPWS do
not adversely affect the sanitary or mineral quality, or the adequacy of a
water supply.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. Approval Process:</H3>

<EM><STRONG>Construction Permit:</STRONG></EM> Applicants must submit an Application for Construction
Permit, together with construction drawings (bearing the seal of an
Illinois registered engineer or architect), specifications and an
engineer's design summary.  Applications are reviewed and approved by
Agency engineers if the proposed work will  not adversely affect the
sanitary or mineral quality and adequacy of the water supply. Law requires
the Agency to respond to applications for a permit within 90 days unless a
fee is required, in which case the Agency must respond in 45 days.<P>

<EM><STRONG>Operating Permits:</STRONG></EM> A permit to operate is required before improvements to
an existing water supply may be put in service.  The Agency provides the
required form at the time the construction permit is issued.  The official
custodian of the CPWS must sign the form and confirm that a certified
operator is responsible for the water supply system. The permit holder must
provide satisfactory water sample test results to the Agency.  Applications
are sometimes denied because a CPWS has reached it's expansion limit,
because of  technical flaws in the proposed construction, or because the
CPWS is in violation of a water quality standard.  If denied, an
application may be appealed to the Illinois Pollution Control Board.<P>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Owners and official custodians of CPWS must register with the Agency.  A
CPWS must be under operational control of a certified operator in
responsible charge of the water supply.  Owners/official custodians of a
CPWS are subject to monitoring and reporting requirements administered by
the Agency's Bureau of Water, Compliance Assurance Section.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Application fees for permits to construct,  install or extend water mains:<P>

From 200 to 1,000 feet = $120.<P> 
From 1,000 feet to 5,000 feet = $360.<P>
Over 5,000 feet = $600.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
