<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Illinois Development Credit Corporation License</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>
<H3>I. Business Requirement Profile:
</H3><dl><dd>
Illinois Development Credit Corporation License
</dd></dl><hr>
<H3>II. Agency:</H3>
<dl><dd>
Department of Financial Institutions<br>
Consumer Credit Division<br>
500 Iles Park Place; Suite 500<br>
Springfield, IL 62718<br>
(217) 782-3704<br>
</dd></dl><hr>
<H3>III. Statute:
</H3><dl><dd>
805 Illinois Compiled Statutes 35 (Development Credit Corporation Act)
</dd><P>
<dt><H3>Regulation:</H3>
<dd>
38 Illinois Administrative Code 195 (Illinois Development Credit Corporation Act)
</dd></dl><hr>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<dl><dd>
The purpose of Development Credit Corporations (DCC) is to create a source of business loans, investment and other services not available through conventional commercial lending institutions; to encourage new businesses to locate in Illinois, help rehabilitate existing businesses, and stimulate expansion of businesses that will contribute to the economic welfare of Illinois and the maximum employment of its citizens. An DCC's powers include lending money, but only to borrowers who have been rejected by conventional lenders, as well as borrowing money, buying, improving or selling property to satisfy debts or obligations. A License may be granted to any 3 or more qualified Illinois resident applicants who associate themselves for the purpose of establishing and operating a DCC. Licenses remain effective until the corporation ceases to operate. <P></dd></dl><hr>

<H3>V. Approval Process:</H3>
<dl><dd>

Applicants for a license must file a Certificate of Organization containing information including the names of all stock subscribers, the number of shares subscribed, the name and address of a depository holding funds for the DCC.  Applicants also must file all bylaws or resolutions adopted and the certificate of any depositary  certifying the amount of funds on deposit to the credit or the DCC. <P>

If the Department finds that the application conforms with all requirements, it will indorse and  return a copy of the articles of incorporation to the applicants and the credit corporation is deemed created. A copy of the indorsed articles of incorporation must be filed with the county recorder's office where the DCC is located. The Illinois Development Credit Corporation Act and Rules are available from the Department. Loans made by a DCC must comply with the specific requirements of the Act. A petition to create a DCC may be denied if the good character and general fitness of the applicants cannot be established or if applicants do not meet capital funding requirements.  Denied petitions may be re-submitted. Petitions are usually processed within 4 to 6 months.  <P>
</dd></dl><hr>

<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post Requisites:</H3>
<dl>
<dt><STRONG>Pre-Requisites: </STRONG> <dd>Petitioners must provide credit reports and resumes for all applicants.  There must be at least 10 shareholders of the corporation.  At least $50,000 must have been received in cash for the fully paid stock of the corporation.  Employees with access to the development credit corporation's money or securities must be bonded. <P>

<dt><STRONG>Co-Requisite:  </STRONG><dd>Licensees are subject to an annual examination by the Department. License holders are obliged to maintain a specific cash surplus. <P></dl><hr>

<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<dl><dd>
Application fees include minimal credit reporting fees and fees associated with legal processing.  Annual examination fees are $200 per examiner per day.<P>
</dd></dl>




<HR>
