<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Liquor Licenses for the following categories (Special Events):  Special Event Retailer's License (Not-For-Profit) and Special Use Permit License.</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I. Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Liquor Licenses for the following categories (Special Events):  Special Event Retailer's License (Not-For-Profit) and Special Use Permit License.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Liquor Control Commission<BR>
Licensing Unit<BR>
100 West Randolph, Suite 5-300<BR>
Chicago, Illinois 60601<BR>
(312) 814-2206<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
235 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/5-1 (Illinois Liquor Control Act)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL>
<DD>
Licenses for the categories listed above each have a brief definition provided on the front page of their respective "Application Instruction Sheet."<P>  

<EM><STRONG>Special Event Retailer's License (Not-For-Profit):</STRONG></EM>  This license is required for the sale of liquor at events conducted by educational, fraternal, political, civic, religious, or not-for-profit organizations.  This license allows the holder to purchase alcoholic liquors from an Illinois licensed distributor and in turn to offer the liquor for sale, at retail, for use and consumption on the specific dates designated for the special event named in the license. However,  if the license holder intends to purchase less than $500.00 of alcoholic liquors, then the purchase may be made from a licensed retailer.  Failure to comply may result in a fine of up to $1, 000.00 for the first offense.  Subsequent offenses are a Class 4 felony.<P>

<EM><STRONG>Special Use Permit License:</STRONG></EM>  This license allows an already licensed Illinois liquor retailer to transfer a portion of its alcoholic liquor inventory from its licensed premise to a site designated for a special event.  Selling or serving alcohol at a special event without a Special Use Permit license is subject to a fine of up to $1,000.00 for the first ofense.  Each subsequent offense is a Class 4 felony.<P>

Permits are valid for the event duration only (maximum of 15 calendar days).  A separate application and fee is required for each event theme and each 15-day increment.</DD>
</DD>
</DL>

<HR>
<H3>V. Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Interested parties must complete and file a standard form, Application for Special Event Retailer License (Not-For-Profit) (Form# IL567-0028) or Application for Special Use Permit License (Form# IL567-0050), for the licenses listed above.  The Commission will send a set of instructions to assist the applicant with completion of the form.  If the Commission's licensing staff determines that more information is required, or that the application is incomplete, they will return the forms to the applicant for further information.  Denied applications may be revised and resubmitted to the Commission.  Processing generally takes 2-3 weeks.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisities & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Dram Shop liability insurance to the maximum limits and local licensing authority approval.  Applicants for the Special Use Permit License must have a current, active Retailer's Liquor License.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<PRE>
A.)  Special Event Retailer's License (Not-For-Profit)	$25.00 (maximum of 15 calendar days)

B.)  Special Use Permit License:

		one (1) day or less		$ 50.00
		two (2) days or more	        $100.00 (maximum of 15 calendar days)
</PRE>
</DD></DL>


