<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Approval for Coal Exploration Operations</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Approval for Coal Exploration Operations
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Natural Resources<BR>
Office of Mines & Minerals  (OMM)<BR>
Land Reclamation Division<BR>
300 West Jefferson St. - Suite 300<BR>
P.O. Box 10137<BR>
Springfield, IL 62791-0137<BR>
(217) 782-4970<BR>
TDD:  (217)524-4626<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 720 
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
62 Illinois Administrative Code 1700-1850
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. 	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A Notice of Intent must be submitted to the Office of Mines and Minerals (OMM)  prior to conducting coal exploration involving extraction of less than 250 tons of coal. A permit application is required to be submitted to OMM for those operations involving extraction of greater than 250 tons of coal. <P>

The purpose of the program is to provide assurance that coal exploration operations minimize environmental impacts. <P>

Exploration includes field gathering of data to determine overburden and coal characteristics, as well as other related environmental data prior to surface coal mining and reclamation operations.<P>

Non-compliance with this requirement results in a written Notice of Violation and a potential fine by OMM. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file a "Notice of Intent to Conduct Coal Exploration" for exploration involving extraction of less than 250 tons of coal or an "Application to Conduct Coal Exploration" for exploration involving extraction of greater than 250 tons of coal together with the appropriate Oil & Gas Division forms.<P>

The average processing time for the "Notice of Intent to Conduct Coal Exploration" is 2 weeks;  an "Application to Conduct Coal Exploration" takes 3 months. <P>

If approved, only operations specified in the notice or permit may be conducted. Applicant must use exploration methods that will minimize environmental impact and reclaim any disturbed areas as outlined by the performance standards. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. 	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Operators planning to conduct exploration may be required to submit an "Application for a Test Hole Permit (Form #OG-7) or a "Test Hole Plugging Record (Form #OG-8) for each section involved. Operators must have a $25,000 Blanket Surety Bond on file with the Oil & Gas Division for coal exploration involving less than 250 tons.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
No fees are required to the Land Reclamation Division, but the Oil & Gas Division requires a permit fee of $100 per section.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
