<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Fur-Bearing Mammal Breeder/Possession Permit</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>
<H3>  I.  Business Requirement Profile:
    </H3><DL><DD>
Fur-Bearing Mammal Breeder/Possession Permit
                 </DD></DL><HR><H3>
II.  Agency:                       </H3>
                                        <DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Natural Resources        <BR>
Conservation Division<BR>
Fur-Bearing Mammal Permit<BR> 
524 S. 2nd Street, Room 210  <BR>
P. O. Box 19458                 <BR>
Springfield, IL 62794-9458          <BR>
(217) 785-3423                          <BR>
                                            </DD></DL><HR><H3>
III. Statute:                                                </H3>
<DL><DD>
520 Illinois Compiled Statutes 5/3.25.
        </DD></DL><HR><H3>
IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
                                  <DL><DD>
A permit from the Department is required for any individual to "hold, possess or engage in the breeding or raising of live fur-bearing mammals".  A permit must be obtained before purchasing a species and species can be obtained only from another licensed breeder.  

Only eleven species are authorized for possession by this permit.  They are: Badger, Beaver, Gray Fox, Red Fox, Muskrat, Mink, Raccoon, River Otter, Opossum, Least Weasel and Long-tailed Weasel.

It is illegal to take a species in the wild, and this permit does not authorize taking animals from the wild.  (Note:  1. A Permit does not authorize possession of striped skunk, bobcat or coyote, and possession of those fur-bearing species is prohibited.  2. A permit may not be required for breeding, raising and producing in captivity, and marketing by the producer, of Mink, Red Fox or Arctic Fox as live animals or as animal pelts or carcasses.  Such activity may be deemed to be an agricultural pursuit and persons so engaged may be considered "fur Farmers".  For complete details consult the Department at the address shown above.)

Permits are issued for a period of up to one year and expire on March 31 after the date of issue.
       </DD></DL><HR><H3>
V.   Approval Process:   </H3>
                              <DL><DD>
Applicant must complete and file with the Department a "Fur-Bearing Mammal Breeder/Possession Permit Application", together with the required fees. Applicant must swear that the information contained thereon  is true and accurate. False or deceptive information may subject applicant to arrest and revocation of license privileges for up to five years.

Licenses are issued approximately two weeks after a properly completed application and fees are received by the Department.  Common reasons for denial are applications that name a species not authorized a species obtained from an unlicensed breeder, and incomplete applications.
                                      </DD></DL><HR><H3>
VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post Requisites:   </H3><DL><DD>

None.                                                                </DD></DL>
 <HR><H3>
VII. Fees:</H3>
               <DL><DD>
Annual fee for a permit is $25.
                       <P>
Make checks or money orders payable to the Department of Natural Resources. 
                          </DD></DL>






<HR>
