<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Ginseng Dealer License, Ginseng Grower License, Ginseng Harvester License. </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>
 <H3>
  I. Business Requirement Profile:
     </H3><DL><DD>
Ginseng Dealer License, Ginseng Grower License, Ginseng Harvester License. 
                  </DD></DL><HR><H3>
II.  Agency:                        </H3>
                                         <DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Natural Resources         <BR>
Conservation Division, Commercial License/Permit     <BR>
524 South Second Street, Room 210                        <BR>
P. O. Box 19458                                              <BR>
Springfield, IL  62794-9458                                      <BR>
(217) 785-3423                                                       <BR>
</DD></DL><HR><H3>
III. Statute:     </H3>
                       <DL><DD>
525 Illinois Compiled Statutes 20.
                               </DD></DL><H3>
Regulation:                                  </H3><DL><DD>

17  Illinois Administrative Code 1580.                    </DD></DL><HR><H3>

IV.  Requirement Description:</H3> 
                                  <DL><DD>
Ginseng Dealer license is required for each individual ("individual" is defined as a person, partnership or corporation), at each location, engaged in the purchase of ginseng from growers or harvesters. 

Ginseng Grower license is required to grow cultivated ginseng in Illinois. Cultivated ginseng is defined as ginseng grown "in tilled beds under shade of artificial structures or under natural shade".

Ginseng Harvester license is required  for (and must be in the possession of) persons when engaged in harvesting or digging wild ginseng, in Illinois.  
                                          </DD></DL><HR><H3>
V.   Approval Process:                                      </H3>
<DL><DD>                                                                 
Applicants must file a "Commercial License/Permit Application" together with appropriate fees for a: 

Dealer License, which is issued for a period  of one year and is valid from April 1 on the year of issue until the following March 31.

Grower License, which is issued for a period of one year and is valid from April 1 of the year of issue until the following March 31.

Harvester License, which  may be purchased from some vendors of  hunting and fishing licenses, or may be obtained by mail from the Illinois Department of Natural Resources.  

Harvest season for wild ginseng begins on the last Saturday in August and ends November 1 annually.  Wild ginseng may be sold only to licensed Illinois ginseng dealers, and only during a period that begins two weeks after the opening day of the harvest season and ends on the following March 1.
        </DD></DL><HR><H3>
VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post Requisites: 
                          </H3>                       <DL><DD>
Ginseng Dealers must keep records (on forms provided by the Department) of certain information regarding ginseng purchases, mail them to the Department each month in which purchases are made, and keep duplicate copies in order to receive certification of ginseng for sale and shipment. (All ginseng purchased by a licensed Illinois dealer must be certified by an agent of the Department before it may be sold or shipped.)

Growers must keep records describing the location and  size of their cultivated ginseng stands on forms provided by the Department; a written  harvest record of cultivated ginseng and an annual report of harvest must be submitted to the Department either upon the sale of the season's crop, or on April 1 of the following year (whichever comes first).

Licenses and permits usually are issued within one week after applications and fees are received by the Department. The most common reason for denial of applications is the failure of applicant to sign the forms.
</DD></DL><HR><H3>
VII. Fees:        </H3>
                       <DL><DD>
<DT>Dealer License: <DD> $50 per year for residents, $100 per year for non-residents. 
<DT>Grower License:  <DD>     $25 per year.
<DT>Harvester License:<DD>    $7.50 per year
                          <P>
Make check or money order payable to Department of Natural Resources.
                             </DL>





<HR>
