<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Surface Mining Permit for Minerals other than Coal</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Surface Mining Permit for Minerals other than Coal
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Natural Resources<BR>
Office of Mines & Minerals<BR>
Land Reclamation Division<BR>
524 South Second Street<BR>
Springfield, IL 62701-1787<BR>
(217) 782-4970<BR>
TDD:  (217) 524-4626<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	 Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 715 (Surface Coal Mining Land Conservation & Reclamation Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
62 Illinois Administrative Code 300.10-180
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A permit is required for mine operators who will affect greater than 10 acres per year or for sites which contain greater than 10 feet of overburden (rock and other earth materials lying above the minerals to be mined) overlaying the mineral to be mined.<P>

This criteria allows many operations to be exempt, however the Office of Mines & Minerals (OMM) should be contacted for confirmation.<P>

The purpose of this Act is to provide public and environmental protection from the effects of surface mining. Violations of this Act are subject to fines of $50 - $1000 per day. <P>

Failure to adhere  to the regulations can also result in forfeiture of the surety bond. <P>

Permits are issued for a 3 year period to uncover the mineral, but do not limit the time period to remove the mineral. Reclamation of the site is required after the permit site is inactive. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file a "Surface Mining Application", form #MLCR-1 to OMM and the county clerk of the county in which the mine is located. Average processing time is 90 days, however it may be extended if a public hearing is requested. The county board has 45 days to request a public hearing or make comments. Failure to respond to requests for additional information, payment of permit fees, or providing of surety bonds are all common reasons for denial. An applicant has the opportunity to submit additional information after a permit denial in an attempt to satisfy the regulatory requirements.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. 	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Approved permittees must file a surety bond to cover the cost of reclamation, which is determined by OMM. <P>

Other permits which may be required include a mining permit and/or (NPDES) water discharge permit from the Illinois EPA. A Department of Natural Resources (DNR) - Office of Water Resource Management Permit is required if the mine is located in a floodplain. Surface mining permits are also subject to DNR endangered species consultation review. This may precede or be concurrent with the OMM  application process.  <P>

Federal permits which may be involved include Army Corps of Engineers (404) permits and the Mine Safety and Health Administration (MSHA). Permittees must file their approved reclamation plans with the county clerk. Annual affected acreage reports must also be filed with the OMM and with the county clerk. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A one-time fee of $100 per acre is required for a surface mining permit. <P>

An annual registration fee of $300 per operator plus $100 per active mining site, plus $250 per active blasting site also is required.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
