<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Dietitian & Nutrition Counselor License</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>
<H3> I.   Business Requirement  Profile:
    </H3><DL><DD>
Dietitian & Nutrition Counselor License
                 </DD></DL><HR><H3>
II.  Agency:                       </H3><DL><DD>

Department of Professional Regulation           <BR>
Licensing & Testing Division / Health Services Section<BR>
320 West Washington                                       <BR>
Springfield, IL 62786                                         <BR>
(217) 524-7540                                                    <BR>
</DD></DL><HR><H3>
III. Statute:     </H3>
                      <DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 1992, 3/1 - 3/200
                              </DD></DL><H3>
Regulation:                                 </H3><DL><DD>

Title 68 Illinois Administrative Code Chapter VII, Subchapter b, Part 1245
                                                         </DD></DL><HR><H3>
IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
                                  <DL><DD>
A License is required to practice as a Dietitian or Nutrition Counselor or to engage in nutrition services.  

Operating as a Dietitian or Nutrition Counselor without a license is a Class A misdemeanor for the first offense and a Class 4 Felony for each subsequent offense.  

Licenses are valid for two years and may be renewed.
                                          </DD></DL><HR><H3>
V.   Approval Process:                                      </H3>
<DL><DD>
Interested persons must contact the Department for an application form.  Applicants must pass a written exam.  The Department or its designated testing agency screens applicants to determine eligibility for examination.  Denial of eligibility to take the exam usually is based on deficient education or experience.  If applicants are licensed as a dietitian or nutrition counselor in another state, the Department may grant a license without an examination.
        </DD></DL><HR><H3>
VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:
                          </H3><DL><DD>
<UL><LI>Dietitian:  Applicants must have a baccalaureate or post-baccalaureate degree in human nutrition, foods and nutrition, dietetics, food systems management, nutrition education, or an equivalent major course of study.  Applicants also must have completed a dietetic internship or have practice experience in dietetics of at least 900 hours.
<P>
<LI>Nutrition Counselor:   Applicants must have a baccalaureate or post-baccalaureate degree in human nutrition, food sciences, home economics, biochemistry, physiology, public health, or an equivalent major course of study.  Applicants also must have practice experience in nutrition services of at least 900 hours.
As a condition for license renewal, license holders must complete 30 hours of continuing education in dietetics or nutrition services during the 2 years preceding the expiration date of the license.
    <P></UL></DD></DL><HR><H3>
VII. Fees:                    </H3>
                                   <DL><DD>
License Fee                   $100         <BR>
Renewal Fee                   $100             <BR>
Endorsement / Reciprocity Fee $200                 <BR>
Reinstatement Fee             $  25 (plus all lapsed renewal fees.)<BR>
Duplicate License Fee         $  25                                    <BR>

</DD></DL>                                                                  





<HR>
