<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: License for Podiatrist, Temporary Podiatric Physician, Permit for Visiting Professor of Podiatric Medicine, Certification for Podiatry Continuing Education Sponsor</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I. 	Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
License for Podiatrist, Temporary Podiatric Physician, Permit for Visiting Professor of Podiatric Medicine, Certification for Podiatry Continuing Education Sponsor
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. 	Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Department of Professional Regulation<BR>
Licensing & Testing Division<BR>
Professional Services Section, Design Unit<BR>
320 West Washington, 3rd Floor<BR>
Springfield, Illinois 62786<BR>
(217) 785-0877<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III. Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 100/1-45
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Title 68 Illinois Administrative Code, Chapter VII, Subchapter b, Part 1360
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV. 	Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A License is required to practice Podiatric Medicine in Illinois. <P>

A temporary practice license may be issued for those individuals who are otherwise qualified for the regular, continuing license except for completion of one (1) year of post graduate training and completion of a required written examination. Temporary license is valid for one year and may be renewed for an additional year.<P>

A college or university professor of Podiatry who is not currently licensed in Illinois and will be teaching only for a fixed period of time must obtain a Visiting Professor of Podiatry license. This 	license allows a Podiatrist, licensed in another state to provide educational instruction in the practice of Podiatry at the college or university where he or she is employed. This license is valid for a period of one year and may be renewed once. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  	Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants for a Podiatrist license must pass a written examination. The examination consists of three parts, two being conducted by the National Board of Podiatric Medical Examiners and the third administered by the Department.  Application for the license may be made after successful completion of the examination.<P>

Applicants for a Visiting Professor license are not required to take a written examination. <P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI. 	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants for a Podiatrist license must be 21 years of age, have graduated from an approved college of Podiatric medicine, and have a Doctor of Podiatric Medicine degree. <P>

Applicants for a Temporary license must show proof that they are enrolled in a recognized postgraduate training program. <P>

Renewal of licenses requires proof  of 50 hours of approved continuing education.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII. Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Podiatric License 	$250<BR>
Visiting Podiatric Professor	$100<BR>
Temporary Podiatric License	$100<BR>
Continuing Education Sponsor	$500<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
