<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop:  License for Veterinarian and Certificate for Veterinary Technician</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>  I.  Business Requirement Profile: </H3><DL><DD>  License for Veterinarian and Certificate for Veterinary Technician
                                                     </DD></DL><HR><H3>
II.  Agency:</H3><DL><DD>     Department of Professional Regulation<BR>
               Licensing & Testing Division<BR>
               Health Services Section         <BR>
               (217) 524-7540                      <BR>
    </DD></DL><HR><H3>
III. Statute:</H3><DL><DD> 225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 115/1-28
                          </DD></DL><H3>
     Regulation: </H3><DL><DD>Title 68 Illinois Administrative Code, Chapter VII, Subchapter b, Part 1500
                              </DD></DL><HR><H3>
IV.  Requirement Description: </H3><DL><DD>A license is required to practice Veterinary Medicine and Surgery. A certificate is required to assist in the practice of veterinary medicine as a Veterinary Technician. (Veterinary Technicians perform services to assist Veterinarians in the practice of veterinary medicine, except for diagnosing, prognosing, writing prescriptions, or performing surgery on animals.) 
                                           </DD></DL><HR><H3>
V.   Approval Process:</H3><DL><DD> A written examination is required for a Veterinarian license. Applicants should contact the Department and request an application and be prepared to show proof of  graduation from a 4 year course in Veterinarian medicine & surgery.
                                   </DD></DL><HR><H3>
VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3><DL><DD> Before anyone may take the written examination for a license to practice Veterinary Medicine and Surgery, applicants must have graduated from a course of study in Veterinary Medicine and Surgery approved by the Department, and have completed at least 2 years of preveterinary collegiate training. 
                                    </DD></DL><HR><H3>
VII. Fees:</H3><DL><DD> Veterinarian License: $100. <DD>  Veterinarian Technician Certificate: $50
</DD></DL>





