<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Asbestos Inspector's License</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Asbestos Inspector's License
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Office of Health Protection<BR>
Division of Environmental Health / Asbestos Program<BR>
525 West Jefferson St.<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-3517<BR>
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
105 Illinois Compiled Statutes 105/1 et seq. (Asbestos Abatement Act) and P.A. #89-143 (Commercial and Public Buildings Asbestos Abatement Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 855.40, 855.340, & 855, Appendix C Illustration A.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Those who inspect public or private schools (grades 1-12) or commercial or public buildings for the presence or condition of asbestos-containing building materials, must be licensed by the Illinois Department of Public Health (IDPH) as an Asbestos Inspector. This is to ensure that persons who inspect for asbestos are properly qualified. Licensees not adhering to the code face fines which can range with the severity of the violation. Unlicensed persons performing these services are subject to a Class A Misdemeanor. Licenses expire May 15 of each year. Licenses issued after January 15 expire May 15 of the following year. Any changes in the licensee's name, address, place of employment, etc., must be submitted, in writing, to IDPH. 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must submit to IDPH, a completed and signed application for licensure as an Asbestos Inspector; two 1 x 1" photos of applicant (head and shoulders only) with the name of the applicant on the back of the photo (The license will not be issued without the identifying photo.); Inspector's Initial Course certificate; current Inspector Refresher Course certificate, if the initial course certificate has expired; all expired Inspector Refresher Course certificates; written verification of a minimum of 1040 hours of experience inspecting buildings for asbestos-containing materials or a minimum of 3120 hours of experience in direct planning of construction projects and/or construction project inspection must be submitted, and; proof of a high school degree or G.E.D. certificate. IDPH has 60 days to process a license application. Failure to provide all requested information will result in delay of the license. Applications may be denied if an applicant fails to meet the education or experience requirements. Applicants may correct any deficiencies and then reapply.  
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>Pre-Requisites:</STRONG>  Applicants must successfully complete an Inspector's Initial Course, have a minimum of 1040 hours experience inspecting buildings for asbestos-containing materials or a minimum of 3120 hours of experience in direct planning of construction projects and/or construction project inspection, and  have a high school degree or graduate education degree. <P>

<STRONG>Post-Requisites:</STRONG> Applicants are required to complete a one-half day Asbestos Building Inspector refresher course annually.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>Application fee:</STRONG>  $50.<P>

A $15 late fee is charged if the renewal application is not received by May 1.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
