<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Emergency Medical Technicians (EMT) License</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile: </H3>
<DL><DD>
Emergency Medical Technicians (EMT) License
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>  
Office of Health Care Regulation<BR>
Division of Emergency Medical Services and Highway Safety<BR>
525 West Jefferson<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 785-2080<BR>
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
210 Illinois Compiled Statutes 50 (The Emergency Medical Services Systems Act )
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 535 (Emergency Medical Services Code)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
There are 3 levels of Emergency Medical Technician License: <P>

1. EMT-B (Basic)<BR>
2. EMT-I (Intermediate)<BR>
3. EMT-P (Paramedic).<P>

Businesses employing unlicensed personnel as an EMT may have their operations suspended by the Department. Unlicensed individuals performing EMT responsibilities are guilty of a Class C misdemeanor.<P>

All licenses are valid for 4 years.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
EMT-B applicants must complete an approved course in basic life support services and pass a written state examination.  An applicant can take the exam up to 3 times in one year. <P>

EMT-I applicants must complete an approved course in specific advanced life support-mobile intensive care services,  a supervised field internship and pass a written examination.  <P>

EMT-P applicants must be a licensed EMT-B or EMT-I, pass a written exam, complete a Department approved course and a supervised field internship on an EMS system vehicle. The EMT-P candidate has 1 year after passing the exam to complete the internship requirements.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites: </H3>
<DL><DD>
To become licensed as an EMT-I requires 160 hours of continuing education every 4 years with 2 refresher courses or 2 Basic Trauma Life Support/Pre-hospital Trauma Life Support (BTLS/PHTLS) courses or one refresher and one BTLS/PHTLS course and a current CPR card.<P> 

To become an EMT-P requires an additional 160 hours of continuing education, a current CPR card and 2 refresher courses or 2 BTLS/PHTLS courses or 1 refresher course and 1 BTLS/PHTLS course every 4 years. EMT-P's must accrue 160 hours of continuing education and maintain a current CPR card every 4 years to remain licensed.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>Testing fees:</STRONG>   EMT-B is $10,   EMT-I is $15,   EMT-P is $25.
</DD></DL>


<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
