<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Food Processing Program; Salvage Warehouse and Store Program; Foodservice Sanitation Manager Certification Program</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>


<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Food Processing Program; Salvage Warehouse and Store Program; Foodservice Sanitation Manager Certification Program
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Division of Food, Drugs and Dairies / Office of Health Protection<BR>
Food Program<BR>
535 West Jefferson St.<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-7532<BR>    
TDD: 1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
410 Illinois Compiled Statutes 620/1 (Illinois Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act);<BR>
240 Illinois Compiled Statutes 30/.01(Salvage Warehouse & Salvage Warehouse Store Act); 
<BR>410 Illinois Compiled Statutes 625/.01(Food Handling Regulation Enforcement Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 730, 725 and 750
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>Food Processing Program:</STRONG>  All processors of food items, except meat and poultry items, are inspected and regulated by the Department. (Meat and poultry items are inspected and regulated by the Illinois Department of Agriculture.)  No Permit or registration is required to operate a food processing facility. However, those entities are required to be inspected annually by the Department prior to operation. (Parties interested in operating a food processing plant should contact the local government to see if a business license is required.) Salvage Warehouse and Salvage Warehouse Store Program:  A Permit is required to operate a Salvage Warehouse or Salvage Warehouse Store (any establishment used to receive, store or re- distribute partially damaged food, alcoholic liquor, drugs, medical devices or cosmetics. Damage may be the result of a fire, flood, storm, train or truck wreck, manufacturer close-out, etc.) 
Permits are valid for 1 year. Warehouses or stores are inspected twice a year.<P>

<STRONG>Foodservice Sanitation Manager Certification Program:</STRONG>  The majority of foodservice (restaurant) establishments in Illinois fall under the jurisdiction of a county/local health department. However, State law and rules require foodservice establishments to employ a Certified Foodservice Sanitation Manager. The Foodservice Sanitation Manager Certification is valid for 5 years.<P>   
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Food processing establishments must request a Department inspection  prior to beginning production. If the facility does not pass inspection the Department will provide a list of all problems and the applicant will have the opportunity to correct them.<P> 

Those proposing to operate a salvage warehouse or warehouse store, must file a "Salvage Warehouse or Salvage Warehouse Store Application". The application takes approximately 30 days to process.  The Department will inspect the facility and issue a License if it passes.  If the facility does not pass inspection an opportunity will be given to the applicant to correct any problems.  To receive a Foodservice Sanitation Manager certificate, applicants must complete a 16-hour IDPH-approved course, an exam and submit an "Application for Foodservice Sanitation Manager Certification" to be eligible for certification.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
None.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Salvage Warehouse and Warehouse Store Permit fee: $100.  An inspection fee is based upon the square footage of the facility. Foodservice Sanitation Manager Certificates are $35.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
