<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Lead Abatement Contractor/Supervisor's License</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.    Business Requirement Profile: </H3>
<DL><DD>
Lead Abatement Contractor/Supervisor's License
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.   Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Office of Health Protection<BR>
Division of Environmental Health / Lead Abatement Program<BR>
525 West Jefferson St.<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-5830<BR>   
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3> 
<DL><DD>
410 Illinois Compiled Statutes 45/1 et seq. (Lead Poisoning Prevention Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 845.28  (Lead Poisoning Prevention Code)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Contractors conducting the destruction or disturbance of any leaded surface in dwellings or day-care facilities must be Licensed Lead Abatement Contractors; the work must be supervised by a Licensed Lead Abatement Contractor/Supervisor and the workers must be Licensed Lead Abatement Workers.<P>

Acting as a Lead Abatement Contractor/Supervisor without a license is Class A misdemeanor.<P> 

Licenses are effective for 1 year, and expire March 31 (except that Licenses issued after December 31 and before April 1 expire the following March 31.)<P>
</DD></DL>  

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants for a lead abatement contractor/supervisor license must file an application for a license as a lead abatement contractor/supervisor together with a certificate of completion from an Illinois approved lead abatement contractor/supervisor 4-day (32 hr.) course and a 1x1" photograph of the applicant. (Applicants licensed or certified in another state may request reciprocal licensure. The Department issues a license if it determines that the requirements for a license in the other state are equal to or greater than its requirements.)<P> 

If an application is denied, the applicant can attempt to correct any deficiency and reapply.<P>

Applications to renew a lead abatement contractor/supervisor license require a 1x1" photo of the applicant and a certificate of completion of an Illinois-approved refresher lead abatement contractor/supervisor 8 hour course.<P> 

Applications are usually processed in 3 - 4 days.<P>

The most common reason for denial of the license application is missing or incorrect information.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.    Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
All contractors are required to take an 8-hour Department approved refresher course annually to qualify for license renewal.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>Application fee for lead abatement contractor/supervisor license:</STRONG> $50. Duplicate licenses are $15.<P> 

<STRONG>Out-of-state applicants for a reciprocal lead abatement contracto/supervisor license:</STRONG> $50.<P> 

<STRONG>Renewal fee for a lead abatement contractor/supervisor license:</STRONG> $50.<P> 

If a renewal application is received after March 1, the applicant also must pay a late fee of $15.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
