<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Lead Abatement Worker's License</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.   Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Lead Abatement Worker's License
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Office of Health Protection<BR>
Division of Environmental Health / Lead Abatement Program<BR>
525 West Jefferson<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-5830<BR>     
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
410 Illinois Compiled Statutes 45/1 et seq. (Lead Poisoning Prevention Act) 
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 845 (Lead Poisoning Prevention Code)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A Lead Abatement Contractor must be licensed before working to destroy or disturb any leaded surface, and those contractors must use licensed Lead Abatement Workers under the supervision of a licensed Lead Abatement Contractor/Supervisor.<P> 

Failure to comply with these requirements is a Class A misdemeanor. <P>

Licenses are valid for 1 year and expire March 31 (except licenses issued after December 31 and before April 1, which expire the following March 31).<P>	
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.   Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file an application for a Lead Abatement Worker License, together with a certificate of completion of an Illinois-approved Lead Abatement Worker three day (24 hour) course, and a 1x1" photo. Applicants licensed or certified in another state may request a reciprocal license. (The Department will issue the license if it determines the requirements in the other state are equal or greater than those in  Illinois. Additional training may be required.)<P> 

To renew a license, applicants must submit an application, 1x1" photo and a certificate of completion of an Illinois-approved Refresher Lead Abatement Worker 8-hour/1 day course. 
The average processing time for a Lead Abatement Worker License application is 3 - 4 days. <P>

The most common reason for denial of applications is missing or incorrect information.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.   Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:  </H3>
<DL><DD>
All lead abatement workers are required to take an 8-hour IDPH-approved Refresher Lead Abatement Worker Course each year to qualify for license renewal.
</DD></DL> 

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>Application fee for Lead Abatement Worker License:</STRONG> $25.<P> 

<STRONG>Out-of-state applicants for a reciprocal Lead Abatement Worker License fee:</STRONG> $25. Renewal license fee: $25.<P>

If a renewal application is received after March 1, applicant must pay $15 in addition to the renewal fee of $25.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
