<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Plumbing ProgramALIGN=ABSBOTTOM </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business Requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Plumbing Program
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II.  Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Office of Health Protection / Plumbing Section<BR>
525 West Jefferson<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 524-0791<BR>
TDD:  1-800-547-0466 (hearing impaired use onl<y)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
225 Illinois Compiled Statutes 320/0.01 et seq. (Illinois Plumbing Licensing Law)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 890 (Illinois Plumbing Code)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A license is required for any business or individual performing plumbing* services.  The purpose of the license is to protect the health of the public from unsafe plumbing by requiring that safe plumbing principles be used.  Except for individuals performing plumbing in his or her own residence, all planning and designing of plumbing systems and all plumbing may be performed only by licensed plumbers, or licensed apprentice plumbers under the supervision of a licensed plumber. *Plumbing generally includes all piping, fixtures, appurtenances and appliances for a supply of water for all purposes, including lawn sprinkler systems from the source of a private water supply on the premises or from the main in the street, alley or at the curb to any buildings where persons live, work or assemble.<P>

Violations may be referred to the State's Attorney or Attorney General. All plumbers' licenses expire on April 30th each year.  A plumber's license and an apprentice plumber's license may be renewed for a period of 1 year.  Renewal applications must be submitted to the Department. An apprentice plumber's license expires the date the licensed plumber sponsor severs sponsorship.<P> 
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Apprentices must file an "Application for Licensure as a Plumbing Apprentice", which the Department usually processes in 5-10 days.   Apprentices with 4 years apprentice work must pass the Illinois State Plumbing Exam to become a licensed plumber. Applicants may be denied eligibility to take the state exam for reasons such as not meeting the requirements or too many people may have already registered to take the exam. Applicants may reapply if they are denied. </DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
To become a plumber an applicant must have served at least 4 years, but no more than six years, as a Licensed Apprentice Plumber. Apprentice plumbers must be at least 16 years of age, have completed 2 years of high school or equivalent and be sponsored by a licensed plumber. A licensed apprenticeship is required prior to taking the exam to become a plumber.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>Apprentice Plumber's License Fee:</STRONG> $50.<P>  

<STRONG>Plumber's License Exam Fee for Illinois Apprentice Plumbers:</STRONG> $100. (When applicant is Registered or Licensed in another state:  $125.)<P> 

<STRONG>Plumber's License Fee:</STRONG> $100.<P>  

<STRONG>Late Fees or Reinstatement Fees for any license renewal:</STRONG> $25.<P> 

<STRONG>Restoration of a Plumber's Expired License Fee (includes the fee for the 1st exam only):</STRONG> $500.<P>

<STRONG>Duplicate Licenses are $25.</STRONG><P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
