<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Swimming Pool, Water Slides and Bathing Beaches</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.  Business requirement Profile:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Swimming Pool, Water Slides and Bathing Beaches
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>II. Agency:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Illinois Department of Public Health<BR>
Division of Environmental Health / Office of Health Protection<BR>
Swimming Pool and Bathing Beach Program<BR>
525 West Jefferson<BR>
Springfield, IL 62761<BR>
(217) 782-5830 <BR>
TDD:  800-547-0466 (for hearing impaired use only)<BR>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>III.  Statute:</H3>
<DL><DD>
210 Illinois Compiled Statutes 125/1-28 (Swimming Pool & Bathing Beach Act)
</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation:</H3>
<DL><DD>
77 Illinois Administrative Code 820 (Swimming Pool & Bathing Beach Code)
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>IV.  Requirement Description:</H3>
<DL><DD>
A permit is required from the Department before a new  swimming pool or
bathing beach may be constructed or altered in a major way.<P>

A license from the Department is required before operating a public
swimming pool or bathing beach. Operators of waterslides must conform to
the requirements of this law and code.<P>

Licenses are valid for 1 year and are renewable upon expiration.<P>

Operating these facilities without a license is a Class A misdemeanor.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>V.  Approval Process:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Applicants must file with the Department an application to construct a pool
or beach together with plans bearing the seal of a Registered Professional
Engineer or Architect.  A permit must be issued before construction may
begin.<P>

The Department usually reviews plans within 3 weeks.<P>

When the construction is completed, the Department will inspect the
facility. At that time applicants must submit an application for licensure
to operate a public swimming pool or bathing beach. Applications usually
take 2 weeks to process.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VI.  Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:</H3>
<DL><DD>
Operators must report to the Department any deaths and injuries that occur
at a licensed facility if they require a physician's care.  The Department
or an approved agent (such as the local health department) inspects each
pool and beach annually to determine eligibility for license renewal based
on compliance with the rules.
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<H3>VII.  Fees:</H3>
<DL><DD>
<STRONG>Construction permit fees for pools with less than 50,000 gallons:</STRONG> $25.<P>

<STRONG>For pools with more than 50,000 gallons:</STRONG> $50.<P>

<STRONG>Bathing beach permit fees:</STRONG> $50.<P>

Annual license fees are $50 and there is a $20 late fee. Not-for-profit
corporations are exempt from all fees except late fees if they provide the
required documentation. Governmental entities  also are exempt from all
fees.<P>
</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
