<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>First Stop: Service Occupation Tax Service Use Tax (Out-of-State)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#004080" LINK="#004080" VLINK="#0080C0" ALINK="#0080C0">

<img src="/dcca/graph/fs/fslogosm.gif" alt="First Stop Logo" width=171 height=120 align=left>
<h3 align=center>Department of Commerce & Community Affairs
<hr>
First Stop Business Information Center<br>
Business Requirement
</h3>
<hr>
<br clear=all>

<H3>I.	Business Requirement Profile:	</H3>
<DL><DD>Service Occupation Tax Service Use Tax (Out-of-State)</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>II.	Agency:  </H3>
<DL><DD>Illinois Department of Revenue<BR>
101 West Jefferson St.<BR>
Springfield, IL 62794<BR>
Taxpayer Services Bureau<BR>
Central Registration Division<BR>
(217) 785-3707</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>III.	Statute:  </H3>
<DL><DD>35 Illinois Compiled Statutes, 115/1</DD></DL>
<H3>Regulation: </H3>
<DL><DD>86 Illinois Administrative Code, Section 140.101.</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>IV.	Requirement Description: </H3>
<DL><DD><P>Service Occupation Tax or Service Use Tax is imposed on persons who repair or otherwise service tangible personal property belonging to others, and transfer merchandise as an incident to providing such service.  (An example is service persons who repair vehicles, appliances, shoes).  Businesses and individuals responsible for collecting and remitting the Service Occupation Tax or Service Use Tax must register with the Department.

<P>Conducting business without registering is a Class A Misdemeanor, and failure to collect and remit the tax may result in penalties including, but not limited to: A tax lien against property, Garnishment of wages and bank accounts, recommendation of professional license revocation, civil judgments, revocation of business certificates of registration, withholding of state warrants, seizure and sale of assets, nonrenewal of corporate charter and/or criminal prosecution.

<P>A certificate of registration grants authority to collect Service Occupation Tax or Service Use Tax and remains effective for 5 years.  If the business remains in compliance, the Department will automatically renew a certificate.</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>V.	Approval Process: </H3>
<DL><DD>To become registered, an applicant must complete and file with the Department an Illinois Business Taxpayer Registration Application (NUC-1).  The average processing time is 3 weeks.</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>VI.	Pre-Requisites, Co-Requisites & Post-Requisites:  </H3>
<DL><DD>Certificate holders must file an annual report form ST-1 / ST-2.  A Federal Employer Identification Number (FEIN) may be required.</DD></DL>
<HR>
<H3>VII.	Fees: </H3>
<DL><DD>There is no registration fee.</DD></DL>

<HR>
<STRONG>| <a href="/dcca/home.htm">DCCA Home Page</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsm1.htm">First Stop</a> | <A HREF="/dcca/menus/fsbr.htm">Business Requirements</a> |</STRONG>

</BODY>
</HTML>
